rank Gresham\n |WrittenBy='''Slave Mart''' & '''Cool for Cramp'''<br />Andrew Brenner\n |OriginalAirDate={{start date|2006|7|29}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=66B3FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=50\n |EpisodeNumber2=4\n |Title=Just Desserts / Pirate Pants\n |DirectedBy='''Just Desserts''' & '''Pirate Pants'''<br />Frank Gresham\n |WrittenBy='''Just Desserts:''' Sean Veder<br />'''Pirate Pants:''' Brian Wood\n |OriginalAirDate={{start date|2006|8|19}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=66B3FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=51\n |EpisodeNumber2=5\n |Title=Neigh Means Neigh / Miner Mishaps\n |DirectedBy='''Neigh Means Neigh''' & '''Miner Mishaps'''<br />Frank Gresham\n |WrittenBy='''Neigh Means Neigh:''' Randolph Heard<br />'''Miner Mishaps:''' Andrew Brenner\n |OriginalAirDate={{start date|2006|8|26}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=66B3FF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=52\n |EpisodeNumber2=6\n |Title=Happy Gas / Twin Toys\n |DirectedBy='''Happy Gas''' & '''Twin Toys'''<br />Frank Gresham\n |WrittenBy='''Happy Gas''' & '''Twin Toys'''<br />Brian Wood\n |OriginalAirDate={{start date|2006|9|2}}\n |ShortSummary=\n |LineColor=66B3FF\n}}\n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Imdb episodes|0299278|The Cramp Twins}}\n\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''The Cramp Twins'' episodes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cramp Twins}}\n[[Category:Lists of British animated television series episodes]]\n[[Category:Lists of American children's animated television series episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Taimoor Yasin Malik", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSeason 1 (2001\u201302)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_The_Cramp_Twins_episodes"}
{"title_page": "Pandora Radio", "text_new": "{{short description|Music streaming and recommendation website}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Pandora\n| logo             = Pandora wordmark.svg\n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| location         = Oakland, California, U.S\n| locations        = 26\n| founder          = Will Glaser <br> [[Jon Kraft]]<br>[[Tlol ok!o loo jyhtgtfgb d's refrigerated terwwaqwzwdddtxtgvgjbhnuhbgbu jjnklkjuhuyygyygghjnjhuuhjjim Westergren]]\n| services         = [[Internet radio]]\n| url              = {{URL|http://pandora.com}}\n| programming_language= [[Java (programming language)|Java]]\n| alexa            = {{decrease}} 634 (January 2019)<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/pandora.com |title= Pandora.com Site Info | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| advertising      = [[Banner ad]]s, video ads, audio ads\n| registration     = Optional (required to save stations)\n| language         = [[English language|English]]\n| native_clients   = [[Universal Windows Platform|Universal Windows App]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|2000|01}} (as Savage Beast Technologies)<br>[[Oakland, California]], U.S.\n| area_served      = United States\n| key_people       = Roger J. Lynch {{small|([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}<ref name=\":0\" /><br>Aim\u00e9e Lapic ([[Chief marketing officer|CMO]])<br>David Gerbitz ([[Chief operating officer|COO]])<br>Chris Phillips ([[Chief product officer|CPO]])\n| num_employees    = 2,200+\n| parent           = [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]]\n| subsidiaries     = [[Rdio]] (as of December 22, 2015), [[Next Big Sound]]\n| num_users        = 71.4 million active (2018),<ref name=PandoraPR02092017>https://finance.yahoo.com/news/pandora-reports-q2-2018-financial-200100666.html</ref> 6.0 million subscribers (2018)<ref name=PandoraPR02092017 />\n| current_status   = Active\n}}\n'''Pandora''' (also known as '''Pandora Media''' or '''Pandora Radio''') is an American [[Comparison of on-demand streaming music services|music streaming]] and automated [[Recommender system|music recommendation]] [[internet radio]] service powered by the [[Music Genome Project]] and headquartered in Oakland, California. The service, operated by [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]], is available in the United States.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|title=Pandora No Longer Available in Australia and New Zealand|url=http://help.pandora.com/customer/portal/articles/2830912|work=Pandora Customer Support|accessdate=July 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713235134/http://help.pandora.com/customer/portal/articles/2830912|archive-date=July 13, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The service plays songs that have similar musical traits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://computer.howstuffworks.com/internet/basics/pandora.htm|title=How Pandora Radio Works|last=Layton|first=Julia|date=|website=HowStuffWorks|access-date=July 23, 2017}}</ref> The user then provides positive or negative feedback (as [[thumbs up]] or [[thumbs down]]) for songs chosen by the service, and the feedback is taken into account in the subsequent selection of other songs to play. The service can be accessed either through a [[web browser]] or with its [[mobile app]]. Pandora is a [[freemium]] service; basic features are free with advertisements or limitations, while additional features, such as improved streaming quality, music downloads and offline channels are offered via paid subscriptions.\n\nIn 2014, Pandora had about 76 million monthly users, and about a 70% share of the internet radio market in the U.S.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://adage.com/article/media/u-s-review-rules-covering-pandora-songwriter-fees/293541/ | title=U.S. to Review Rules Covering Pandora Songwriter Fees | work=[[Advertising Age]] | date=June 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPandora's Promoted Stations rely on its core [[Music Genome Project]]. Overall, the Music Genome Project of more than 450 attributes assigned to each song with a human-curated database of recorded music.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.sfgate.com/technology/article/Pandora-advertisers-hope-to-turn-tunes-into-5470034.php | title=Pandora advertisers hope to turn tunes into dollars | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | first=Benny | last=Evangelista | date=May 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]] acquired Pandora for $3.5 billion in stock.<ref name=completes>{{cite news | url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/sirius-xm-completes-acquisition-of-pandora-1203125882/ | title=Sirius XM Completes Acquisition of Pandora | first=Jem | last=Aswad | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=wraps>{{cite news | url=https://www.bizjournals.com/newyork/news/2019/02/01/sirius-xm-wraps-up-pandora-acquisition.html | title=Sirius XM wraps up Pandora acquisition | first=Anthony | last=Noto | work=[[American City Business Journals]] | date=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Pandora Logo RGB thumbnail new large.png|thumb|upright=0.65|App logo of Pandora]]\nIn 2000, Will Glaser, [[Jon Kraft]] and [[Tim Westergren]] founded the company as Savage Beast Technologies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/on-small-business/when-we-were-small-pandora/2015/02/06/11ad75f4-ad5c-11e4-9c91-e9d2f9fde644_story.html | title=When we were small: Pandora | last=Harrison | first=J. D. | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=February 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.inc.com/magazine/20071001/pandoras-long-strange-trip_pagen_2.html | title=Pandora's Long Strange Trip | first=Stephanie | last=Clifford | work=[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]] | date=October 1, 2007}}</ref> The idea was to create a radio station for each user, with music that the user prefers and without music that they do not prefer. The company ran through its initial $2 million in funding by 2001. Founder [[Tim Westergren]] then convinced Pandora's 50 employees to work for two years without pay.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://thehustle.co/pandora-speech | title=How Pandora\u2019s Founder Convinced 50 Early Employees to Work 2 Years Without Pay | first=Sam | last=Parr | work=The Hustle | date=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nInitially, the company pursued a transitional strategy of licensing technology to companies such as [[AOL]], [[Best Buy]], [[Barnes & Noble]], and [[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]]. In July 2005, the company changed its name to Pandora Media.<ref name=:2>{{cite news | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1230276/000119312511087171/ds1a.htm | title=PANDORA MEDIA, INC. Amendment No. 2 to FORM S-1 | publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]}}</ref>\n\nThe website began as a paid service but quickly changed to an advertiser-sponsored service to make it also available free for users.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://techcrunch.com/2005/11/10/pandora-now-offers-free-option/ | title=https://techcrunch.com/2005/11/10/pandora-now-offers-free-option/ | publisher=[[TechCrunch]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the company went [[public company|public]] via an [[initial public offering]] on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/24/in-the-war-over-tech-ipos-the-new-york-stock-exchange-is-drawing-some-blood/ In The War Over Tech IPOs, The New York Stock Exchange Is Drawing Some Blood] June 24, 2011</ref>\n\nOn March 7, 2013, Pandora chairman and [[chief executive officer]] Joseph J. Kennedy announced that he would leave the company after nine years.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/07/chief-executive-at-pandora-media-to-step-down/ | title=Chief Executive at Pandora Media to Step Down | last=Sisario | first=Ben| work=[[The New York Times]] | date=March 7, 2013 | url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, Pandora announced that its radio streaming service had 200 million users, including 70 million [[monthly active users]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2013/04/09/pandora-hits-200-million-registered-users-in-the-us-nearly-1-5-billion-monthly-listener-hours/ | title=Pandora hits 200 million registered users in the US, 1.5 billion monthly listener hours | last=Wauters | first=Robin | work=[[The Next Web]] | date=April 9, 2013}}</ref> By December 2013, Pandora accounted for 70% of all [[Internet radio]] listening in the United States.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nOn September 1, 2013, Pandora removed a 40-hour-per-month limitation for free mobile listening.<ref name=\"thenextweb1\">{{cite news | url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2013/08/22/pandora-will-remove-its-40-hour-per-month-mobile-listening-cap-on-september-1st/ | title=Pandora will remove its 40 hour per month mobile listening cap on September 1st | work=[[The Next Web]] | date=August 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2015, Pandora removed lyrics from song pages but returned them by July. On April 16, 2015, song samples were removed. At around the same time, a new feature was introduced to give users the ability to receive notices about their favorite artists through the music player. They also redesigned the thumbs up/down feature to allow the listener to undo their action.\n\nBy January 2015, songs played on Pandora had received more than 50 billion thumbs up from users.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://blog.pandora.com/2015/01/29/50-billion-thumbs-3/ | title=50 Billion Thumbs | first=Nicole | last=McInnes | work=Pandora | date=January 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2017, Pandora revealed that 56 million of its 81 million active users subscribe to the ''Today's Country'' station and that [[country music]] accounted for more than 1.7 billion listening hours on the platform in 2016.<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2017/4/27/15451070/pandora-country-music-streaming Can country music save Pandora?] [[The Verge]] Retrieved March 15, 2018</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2017, Pandora discontinued services in Australia and New Zealand, citing a need to focus solely on the U.S. market.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.news.com.au/technology/home-entertainment/audio/pandora-no-longer-available-in-australia-and-new-zealand-heres-what-you-need-to-know/news-story/4d2eddd01342d4dfa2cd7319cb3bf7bf | title=Pandora to leave Australia: Here\u2019s what you need to know | work=[[news.com.au]] | date=July 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7849103/pandora-leaving-australia-new-zealand-markets | title=Pandora Is Winding Down Operations in Australia and New Zealand | first=Marc | last=Schneider | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Roger Lynch became CEO and stated that he wanted to expand the service's focus on [[podcast]]s, with similar discovery features to those for music, as well as new monetization options.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/pandora-podcast-genome-project-1202661263/ | title=Pandora CEO Roger Lynch Wants to Create the Podcast Genome Project | last=Roettgers | first=Janko | work=Variety | date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, Lynch's departure was announced following the approval of Sirius XM's acquisition of Pandora. Lynch will be replaced by Sirius XM CEO Jim Meyer.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pandora-ceo-roger-lynch-exits-786283/ | title=Pandora\u2019s CEO Roger Lynch Exits As SiriusXM Takes Over | last=Wang | first=Amy X. | last2=Wang | first2=Amy X. | work=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 15, 2019, Pandora announced the launch of its own in-app voice assistant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/01/15/pandora-launches-a-personalized-voice-assistant-on-ios-and-android/|title=Pandora launches a personalized voice assistant on iOS and Android|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref>\n\nOn February 26, 2019, Pandora announced the launch of Pandora Stories, a new marketing tool for artists. The feature allows artists to build music playlists combined with voice tracks, where they can add a narrative and deeper insights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/02/26/pandora-stories-launches-combining-music-and-podcasting-in-a-new-format/|title=Pandora Stories launches, combining music and podcasting in a new format|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Pandora's parent company, Sirius XM, signed a multiyear deal with Marvel to launch a series of superhero-based podcasts in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/22/772355077/marvel-expands-its-universe-to-superhero-podcasts-on-siriusxm-and-pandora|title=It's Superhero Time On Podcasts: Star-Lord And Black Widow To Step Up To The Mic|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisitions ===\nOn June 11, 2013, Pandora announced it would purchase FM radio station [[KXMZ]] in [[Rapid City, South Dakota]].<ref name=\"verge-pandorafm\">{{cite web|title=Pandora buys FM radio station in a wily move to fight music labels|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/6/11/4420936/pandora-buys-fm-radio-station-in-a-wily-move-to-fight-music-companies|work=The Verge|accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"hills-pandora\">{{cite web|last=Harrison|first=Christopher|title=Why Pandora bought an FM radio station|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/technology/304763-why-pandora-bought-an-fm-radio-station|date=June 11, 2013}}</ref> On October 7, 2015, Pandora announced it had acquired independent ticketing agency [[Ticketfly]] for $450 million.<ref name=\"ticketfly\">{{cite web|title=Game changer: Pandora confirms $450m acquisition of Ticketfly|url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/game-changer-pandora-confirms-450m-acquisition-ticketfly/|work=musicbusinessworldwide|accessdate=December 30, 2015|date=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, streaming music service [[Rdio]], founded by Skype co-founders [[Janus Friis]] and [[Niklas Zennstroem]], declared bankruptcy and sold its assets to Pandora for $75 million.<ref>By James Risley, GeekWire. \"[http://www.geekwire.com/2015/rdio-to-shut-down-streaming-music-service-sells-assets-to-pandora-for-75m/ Rdio to shut down streaming music service, sells assets to Pandora for $75M].\" November 16, 2015. November 17, 2015.</ref> Pandora retained 100 Rdio employees, including Iain Morris and Rich Masio, who joined a growing licensing department in pursuit of direct licenses with labels and publishers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/can-these-former-rdio-execs-woo-the-music-biz-for-pandora/|title=Can these former Rdio execs woo the music biz for Pandora? - Music Business Worldwide|date=January 25, 2016 |newspaper=Music Business Worldwide|language=en-US |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Pandora announced it would acquire digital audio [[List of advertising technology companies|ad technology firm]] [[AdsWizz]] for $145 million.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/21/pandora-doubles-down-on-ad-tech-with-acquisition-of-adswizz-for-145-million/ | title=Pandora doubles down on ad tech with acquisition of AdsWizz for $145 million | first=Sarah | last=Perez | work=[[TechCrunch]] | date=March 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]] acquired Pandora for $3.5 billion in stock.<ref name=completes/><ref name=wraps/>\n\n== Features ==\n\n=== Streaming ===\n{{More citations needed|section|date=October 2017}}\nThe service has two subscription plans: a free subscription supported by advertisements, and a fee-based subscription without advertisements.<ref name=\":1\" /> Listeners can tune into established [[Music genre|genre]] stations, other users' stations or create their own stations based on their musical interests.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifewire.com/pandora-internet-music-streaming-1847453|title=Guide to Pandora Internet Music Streaming|work=Lifewire|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> Each track played can be responded to with favorable (thumbs up) or unfavorable (thumbs down) buttons, which determine if it and similar songs should be played in the station.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifewire.com/how-pandora-creates-stations-1847393|title=Learn How Pandora Creates Stations and How You Can Customize Them|work=Lifewire|access-date=2018-12-03|language=en}}</ref> A second thumbs down to the same artist will ban that artist from the selected station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techwalla.com/articles/how-to-ban-an-artist-from-one-of-your-stations-on-pandoracom|title=How to Ban an Artist From One of Your Stations on Pandora.com|website=Techwalla}}</ref> A thumbs down immediately skips a song, but the number of times a user can skip tracks is limited unless they are using one of the paid subscription plans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifewire.com/customizing-your-pandora-stations-1847412|title=Hidden Secrets of Customizing Your Pandora Stations|work=Lifewire|access-date=2018-12-03|language=en}}</ref> The free version of Pandora also plays short advertisements between every three or four songs.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThere is a setting in each member's account allowing the user to censor songs with explicit lyrics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/block-explicit-lyrics-in-music-subscription-services/|title=How to block explicit lyrics in streaming music|last=Broida|first=Rick|date=2018-05-23|work=CNET|access-date=2018-12-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile listening, users are offered the ability to buy the songs or albums at various online retailers like iTunes or Amazon.<ref name=\":1\" /> More than 450 musical attributes are considered when selecting the next song.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/28/17172954/pandora-personalized-playlists-automatically-generate|title=Pandora launches automatically generated personalized playlists|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref> These 450 attributes are combined into larger groups called focus traits, of which there are 2,000.<ref name=\":4\">{{Citation|last=Miller|first=Michael|title=Playing Music on Pandora|date=2015-06-01|url=http://www.informit.com/articles/article.aspx?p=2337783|access-date=2018-12-03}}</ref> Examples of these are rhythm [[syncopation]], key [[tonality]], and vocal [[harmonies]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn October 2014, less than 5 percent of active listeners were paying subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/2592715-pandora-medias-p-ceo-brian-mcandrews-on-q3-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript?part=single |title=Pandora Media's (P) CEO Brian McAndrews on Q3 2014 Results \u2013 Earnings Call Transcript |publisher=[[Seeking Alpha]] |date=October 24, 2014}}</ref> At the time of Pandora's [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] in 2011, Pandora had 800,000 tracks from 80,000 artists in its library and 80 million users.<ref>{{cite web|title=With 80 Million Users, Pandora Files To Go Public |url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/02/11/pandora-files-to-go-public/ |publisher=[[TechCrunch]] |date=February 11, 2011}}</ref> By November 2014, Pandora had approximately doubled its library size, topping 1.5 million songs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2014/11/26/366339553/pandoras-new-deal-different-pay-different-play |title=Pandora's New Deal: Different Pay, Different Play |first=Laura |last=Sydell |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=November 26, 2014 |accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> As of end of mid-year 2018, Pandora had 71.4 million active users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/pandora-reports-q2-2018-financial-200100666.html|title=Pandora Reports Q2 2018 Financial Results|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Pandora announced additional features and subscription options, including a mid-level subscription service known as ''Pandora Plus'' that offers advertisement-free streaming, offline playback support using a prediction mechanism and more skips and replays. Users of the free service were also provided more skips and replays in exchange for watching an advertisement. Pandora also announced the launch of an on-demand service similar to competitors such as [[Apple Music]] and [[Spotify]].<ref name=\"engadget-newplans\">{{cite web|title=Pandora relaunches its mid-level $5 monthly subscription tier [Updated]|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/09/15/pandora-relaunches-its-mid-level-5-monthly-subscription-tier/|website=Engadget|publisher=AOL |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/pandora-launches-song-replays-more-skips-for-all/ |title=Pandora launches song replays, more skips for all |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2017, Pandora launched ''Pandora Premium'', a new service allowing users to listen to and create playlists of individual songs on demand. Pandora's suggestions engine suggests and recommends songs and albums, as well as generates playlists based on similar songs. Pandora also emphasized a use of machine learning and manual curation, and that it had filtered \"karaoke tracks, knock-off covers and pet sounds (but not ''[[Pet Sounds]]'') that slow down other services\" from its library.<ref name=\"tc-premium\">{{cite web|title=Pandora\u2019s on-demand music service finally arrives|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/13/pandoras-on-demand-music-service-finally-arrives/|website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Limitations ===\nTo comply with the requirements and protections offered by the [[DMCA]], Pandora serves users only in the United States, using [[IP addresses]] to block users from non-complying countries.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Breaking Pandora's Heart...|url = http://blog.pandora.com/2007/05/03/breaking_pandor/|website = Pandora Blog |accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nInitially, users with free accounts could listen to 40 hours of music a month, and could pay $0.99 per month for unlimited streaming. In September 2011, Pandora removed the 40-hour listening limit.<ref name=\"NewPandora\">[http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2011/09/new-pandora-for.html \"New Pandora for All\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923190211/http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2011/09/new-pandora-for.html |date=September 23, 2011 }}. Pandora Blog. September 22, 2011. Retrieved September 3, 2011.</ref> This 40-hour limit on free listening was re-introduced in March 2013 for mobile devices.<ref>[http://gigaom.com/2013/02/28/pandora-caps-monthly-free-tunes-on-mobiles-to-40-hours/ Pandora caps monthly free tunes on mobiles to 40 hours \u2014 Tech News and Analysis]. Gigaom.com (February 28, 2013). Retrieved January 17, 2014.</ref> However, this limit was removed once more in September of the same year.<ref name=\"thenextweb1\" />\n\nIn September 2016, a rewind function was introduced allowing users to replay a song. The updated streaming service also allowed users to skip an unidentified number of additional songs per hour if they opted to watch an ad. Previous to that, users were only able to skip six songs in an hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/pandora-launches-song-replays-more-skips-for-all/|title=Pandora launches song replays, more skips for all|last=Solsman|first=Joan E.|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Mobile devices ===\n[[File:Pandora-on-iOS.png|thumb|Pandora [[iOS]] App|318x318px]]\nPandora is available on [[iOS]] devices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/pandora-radio/id284035177|title=Pandora Music on the App Store|website=App Store}}</ref> It is ad-supported and retains the original skip limits. Pandora is also available on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] (for tablets and mobile phones),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.pandora.android&hl=en|title=Pandora Music|first=|last=Pandora|date=November 19, 2017|publisher=|via=Google Play}}</ref> and [[BlackBerry 10]] handsets via the Amazon app store.\n\nThe Pandora for [[BlackBerry OS]] (7.1 and earlier) application is limited to AT&T, Sprint, Verizon, T-Mobile, Boost Mobile, and U.S. Cellular carriers, but by visiting the Pandora website directly other BlackBerry users have been successful in downloading and using the application.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.softandapp.com/pandora.html|title=Pandora Radio - Free Download & App Review|website=www.softandapp.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== Technical information ==\nThe Pandora media player is based on [[OpenLaszlo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.openlaszlo.org/showcase#Pandora |title=Showcase |publisher=OpenLaszlo |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024043132/http://openlaszlo.org/showcase#Pandora |archivedate=October 24, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Pandora can also be accessed through many [[digital media receiver|media streaming devices]] such as [[Roku]], Reciva-based radios (from companies like [[Grace Digital]], [[Sanyo]], and [[Sangean]]), Frontier Silicon-based connected audio systems, [[Slim Devices]], [[Sonos]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonos.com/get_music/radio_services/pandora/ |title=Sonos Multi-Room Music System |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421124104/http://www.sonos.com/get_music/radio_services/pandora/ |archivedate=April 21, 2008}}</ref> and [[HEOS by Denon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.denon.com/us/heos |title=HEOS by Denon Wireless Speakers}}</ref> product(s). On July 11, 2008, Pandora launched a mobile version of their software for the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[iPhone]] and [[iPod Touch]] through the [[iTunes App Store]]. Pandora is also available for [[Windows Phone]], [[Windows 10]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] phones,<ref>[http://www.pandora.com/android Pandora Radio is now available to stream music on your Android phone]. Retrieved September 17, 2009.</ref> [[BlackBerry]] platforms, HP [[webOS]] (used on the [[Palm Pre]], [[Palm Pixi]], [[Palm Pre 2]], and [[HP Veer]]) {{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}. Pandora was the provider for [[MSN]] Radio until MSN discontinued their internet radio service on June 18, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msrplans.com/MSN_Drops_Pandora.html |title=Free online radio removed from MSN |publisher=Msrplans.com |date=June 19, 2008 |accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> A modified version of Pandora has been made available for [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]]. Pandora is available on [[Comcast]]'s X1/X2 cable TV products. A GNU/Linux-based application, called Pithos, which is available for accessing Pandora Radio, is available for most distributions via their repositories and is also available to build from source. SoundSpectrum's iOS-based visualizing application Tunr<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.soundspectrum.com/tunr/|title=Tunr - All-in-One Visual Music Player by SoundSpectrum|website=www.soundspectrum.com|language=en-US |accessdate=March 4, 2017}}</ref> has native support for Pandora, but requires a subscription.\n\nWith a subscription to Pandora's One service, Windows and Mac users can download a desktop application for Pandora that uses the [[Adobe Air]] without using a web browser to access Pandora. All the normal functionality is included such as thumbs up/down, skip, pause and access to all channels on a user's account.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lifehacker.com/396393/top-10-apps-worth-installing-adobe-air-for|title=Top 10 Apps Worth Installing Adobe AIR For|last=Purdy|first=Kevin|work=Lifehacker|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Business model ==\nPandora decided to be a consumer-oriented music discovery service, specifically a non-interactive radio station.  In the three months that ended October 31, 2011, advertising comprised 88% of Pandora's total revenues;<ref name=\"sec.gov\">Pandora Media, Inc. \"[https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1230276/000119312511323367/d244588d10q.htm 2011 3rd Quarter Report, SEC Form 10-Q].\" November 29, 2011. Retrieved December 2, 2011.</ref> that was reported as 80% in December 2013.<ref name=\":0\" />  RPM (revenue per 1000s of hours) is determined based on CPMs (cost per thousand impressions). CPMs are largely dependent upon network effects and thus increase as a website scales and adds users. As such, Pandora's strategy in order to allow for widespread distribution was to offer a service unbundled from devices and transport. Pandora also works with system-on-chip manufacturers to embed its technologies on the chips they sell to consumer electronics manufacturers like [[Panasonic]], [[Samsung]], and [[Sony]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2010/10/an-update-on-pa.html/ | title=An Update on Pandora in Your Living Room | accessdate=December 2, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128225153/http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2010/10/an-update-on-pa.html | archivedate=November 28, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPandora's cost structure is highly variable, with content acquisition costs representing roughly 50% of total costs.<ref name=\"sec.gov\" /> There are three main costs associated with content acquisition. First, [[SoundExchange]] collects content fees on behalf of labels or artists on the recording themselves. These are by far the largest content acquisition costs.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}} Second, Pandora pays licensing fees to agencies such as [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]], [[ASCAP]], or [[SESAC]] in order to compensate composers, songwriters and publishers. Lastly, Pandora also pays [[TiVo Corporation]] for song and artist information; this has recently been structured as a flat monthly fee.\n\nHigh variable costs mean that Pandora does not have significant [[operating leverage]], and in the next couple years might actually have negative operating leverage due to an unfavorable shift in product mix towards mobile. Pandora is currently estimated to monetize mobile hours at roughly one-ninth the rate of desktop hours.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-11/pandora-slow-to-lure-mobile-ad-dollars-even-as-ipad-listeners-flock-tech.html/ | title=Pandora Slow to Lure Mobile-Ad Dollars Even as Users Flock | accessdate=December 2, 2011 | work=Bloomberg | first1=Andy | last1=Fixmer | first2=Ari | last2=Levy | date=October 11, 2011}}</ref> Since Pandora pays the same licensing cost per hour irrespective of the user's platform, the net contribution to earnings per mobile hour is even more skewed with respect to contribution to earnings from desktop hours. Mobile revenues will improve over time as Pandora shifts from relying on third-party ad networks to selling ad inventory internally at premium rates.\n\nIn January 2011, Pandora met with [[investment bank]]s to consider a possible $100 million IPO.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN1310587520110113 | work=Reuters | first=Clare | last=Baldwin | title=UPDATE 1-Groupon, Pandora met this week with IPO bankers | date=January 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jay | last=Yarow  |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/pandora-was-saved-by-the-iphone-now-its-thinking-ipo-2010-3 |title=Pandora Was Saved By The iPhone, Now It's Thinking IPO |publisher=[[Business Insider]] |date=March 8, 2010 |accessdate=November 6, 2012}}</ref> The company filed with the SEC for a $100mm IPO on February 11, 2011 and officially began trading on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] with ticker symbol \"P\" on June 15, 2011 at a price of $16/share. This gave them a valuation of nearly $2.6 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cabot.net/News/2011/06/Pandora-IPO.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110731155546/http://www.cabot.net/News/2011/06/Pandora-IPO.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 31, 2011 |title=Internet Radio Company Pandora Sets IPO |publisher=[[Cabot Investing Advice]] |date=June 15, 2011 |accessdate=November 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nPandora announced $80.8 million in total revenue for their first quarter of fiscal 2012, which was up 58% over their previous year Q1 results. Of the $80.8 million, $70.6 million came from advertising, while the other $10.2 million came from subscription. In addition, Pandora has seen a 62% advertising revenue increase, and a 38% subscription revenue increase year-over-year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/05/23/pandoras-quarterly-results-80-8m-in-revenue-52m-active-users-3-09b-listening-hours-per-month/|title=Pandora\u2019s Quarterly Results: $80.8M In Revenue, 52M Active Users & 3.09B Listening Hours|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the vast majority of Pandora's users remain on the free, ad-supported model.\n\n== Royalties ==\nBecause of [[Internet Radio Day of Silence|the passage of DMCA in 1998]] that increased fees and asked for licensing guarantees, the Pandora service was only available in Australia, New Zealand and the [[United States]],<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Breaking Pandora's Heart...\n| url = http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2007/05/breaking_pandor.html\n| publisher = Pandora Blog\n| date = May 3, 2007\n| accessdate = May 7, 2007\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = Canada\n| url = http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2007/05/canada.html\n| publisher = Pandora Blog\n| date = May 14, 2007\n| accessdate = May 15, 2007\n }}</ref> until service to Australia and New Zealand ceased on 1 August 2017 after \"consideration of external factors\".<ref name=\":3\" />  These rulings affect all U.S.-based Internet-based radio stations (terrestrial radio is not affected).\n\nAs of July 2008, Pandora was in talks with major music labels regarding royalty issues to allow a return to the European market.\nCosts remain a concern because of European royalty standards and a low demand for paid music services.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Pandora UK closes after royalties demands\n| url = https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/01/08/pandora_uk_closes/\n| publisher = The Register\n| date = January 8, 2008\n| accessdate = January 8, 2008\n }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the founder of Pandora stated that the company may be on the verge of collapse. Royalty fees account for a majority portion of Pandora's revenues. If an agreement between Pandora and [[SoundExchange]] had not been reached, it could have meant the end of Pandora. \"We're losing money as it is,\" said [[Tim Westergren]]. \"The moment we think this problem in Washington is not going to get solved, we have to pull the plug because all we're doing is wasting money.\"<ref>Peter Whoriskey,[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/15/AR2008081503367.html?hpid=topnews \"Giant of Internet Radio Nears Its 'Last Stand'\"], The Washington Post, August 16, 2008</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2008, a bill was passed by the U.S. House and Senate to allow sites like Pandora to continue negotiations with SoundExchange into 2009.\n\nOn July 7, 2009, Pandora announced that an agreement had been reached regarding the royalty issue, which would significantly reduce the royalty rate, making it possible for Pandora to stay in business. Also announced was that free listening would be limited to 40 hours per month, but can be extended to unlimited for that month for [[United States dollar|USD]]$0.99. \"The revised royalties are quite high,\" the company's blog notes, \"higher in fact than any other form of radio\".<ref>{{cite web|date=July 7, 2009 |url=http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2009/07/important_updat_1.html |title=Pandora: Important update on royalties |publisher=Blog.pandora.com |accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> The extended listening fee differs from \"upgrading\", which also disables advertisements, increases the bitrate from 64 to 192 [[Kbp/s|kbps]], and provides a dedicated music player (as opposed to listening through browser). This service, known as \"Pandora One\", costs $36 and is billed annually.<ref>[http://www.pandora.com/#/account/upgrade/ Unlimited ad-free listening for $36 per year], pandora.com. Retrieved September 17, 2009.</ref> Pandora has since introduced an option to purchase Pandora One subscriptions on a monthly basis at a rate of $3.99 per month.<ref>[http://help.pandora.com/customer/portal/articles/84834-pandora-one Pandora One Cost], pandora.com</ref> Also, in September 2013, Pandora began working with [[HitBliss]] to make Pandora One subscriptions available for HitBliss earned-payment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitbliss.com/pandora.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915051721/http://www.hitbliss.com/pandora.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 15, 2013 |title=Pandora One Subscriptions via |publisher=Hitbliss.com |accessdate=April 8, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nWith an update to the Pandora player in September 2011, the 40 hour cap was extended to 320 hours.<ref name=\"NewPandora\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://mashable.com/2011/09/21/pandora-redesign/ | title=Pandora Unleashes Redesigned Music Player With No Listening Cap | accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn November 22, 2011, Pandora reported its Q3 earnings. Royalty costs accounted for 50% of revenue, slightly better than expected. Its revenue, most of it from advertising, continues to rise at respectable rates. Not only has Pandora attracted more users but the average number of hours per user have also increased. Pandora now accounts for an estimated 4% of total US listening hours. As Pandora grows, it hopes to gain leverage on music labels and drive royalty costs down.<ref>Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry and Henry Blodget, [http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-11-23/research/30432348_1_pandora-higher-revenue-spotify \"Pandora Still Growing Like Gangbusters -- Now 4% Of Total US Radio Listening\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121010144/http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-11-23/research/30432348_1_pandora-higher-revenue-spotify |date=January 21, 2012 }}, Business Insider, November 23, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2011, the CEO of [[Spotify]], [[Daniel Ek]], announced Spotify Radio would offer an unlimited number of stations and unlimited skips. Though Pandora's usage is 70% mobile, the Spotify Radio app competes against Pandora's mobile market.<ref>Henry Blodget and Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry,[http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-12-09/tech/30493388_1_pandora-radio-service-radio-market \"Spotify Announces 'Spotify Radio' -- Presumably A Pandora-Killer\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211015122/http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-12-09/tech/30493388_1_pandora-radio-service-radio-market |date=December 11, 2011 }}, Business Insider, December 9, 2011</ref>\n\nPandora CEO Tim Westergren has supported The Internet Radio Fairness Act or IRFA (H.R. 6480/S. 3609), which would reduce the company's royalty payments to the performers by 80 percent.<ref>{{cite web|last=Orlowski |first=Andrew |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/17/pandora_fairness/ |title=Pandora boss urges 85% pay cut for musicians. |publisher=Theregister.co.uk |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 5, 2012, Pandora filed suit in federal district court against [[ASCAP]] over royalty fees.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/11/5/3606252/pandora-ascap-lawsuit-licensing-fees | title=Pandora sues ASCAP over songwriter fees, asks court to establish 'reasonable' licensing | date=November 5, 2012 | accessdate=November 6, 2012}}</ref> In the suit, the company sought to advocate for lower licensing fees on all the songs represented by the ASCAP's 435,000 members.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-11-05/pandora-media-sues-ascap-seeking-lower-songwriter-fees.html | title=Pandora sues ASCAP Seeking Lower Songwriter Fees | date=November 5, 2012 | accessdate=December 5, 2012 | work=Bloomberg}}</ref>  On February 27, 2013, Pandora announced a 40-hour-per-month limit on free mobile listening. Pandora CEO Tim Westergren cited escalating royalty costs as the reason for the mobile cap.<ref>Tim Westergren, [http://blog.pandora.com/2013/02/27/a-note-to-our-listeners/ \"A note to our listeners\"], Pandora.com, February 27, 2013</ref>\n\nIn a ruling made public in March 2014, US District Judge Denise Cote ruled that Pandora's rate paid to ASCAP should remain the same, 1.85%. She cited (p.&nbsp;97) \"troubling coordination\" between two of the biggest publishing companies (Sony and UMPG) and ASCAP that alludes to core antitrust concern in the industry.<ref>UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, Plaintiff, v. AMERICAN SOCIETY OF COMPOSERS, AUTHORS, AND PUBLISHERS, Defendant. 97. United States District Court, Southern District of New York. March 18, 2014. Title 17: The S(c)ite For Copyright Law. Paul Fakler, March 19, 2014. Web. November 23, 2014.</ref>\n\nAfter arguing that both ASCAP and BMI were showing bias towards international broadcasters who own terrestrial radio stations, Pandora announced on June 11, 2013 that it would attempt to acquire [[KXMZ]], a radio station in South Dakota, under the presumption that doing so would allow it to access the same preferential licensing terms offered to services such as [[iHeartRadio]] (which is owned by [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]], itself America's largest radio broadcaster).<ref name=verge-pandorafm /><ref name=\"hills-pandora\" /> The move was criticized by David Israelite, CEO of the [[National Music Publishers Association]], who declared that Pandora was now \"at war with songwriters,\" and had lost its credibility because it was resorting to \"lawsuits and gimmicks\" to make its point. However, a member of [[Public Knowledge]] praised the move, by stating that it was \"a perfect example of the twisted incentives and strange results we get from a music licensing system that is based on who wants a license instead of just what they want to do with the music they\u2019re using.\"<ref name=verge-pandorapublisher>{{cite web|title=CEO of top music publishers' trade group says Pandora is at war with songwriters|work=The Verge|accessdate=June 13, 2013|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/6/12/4424796/music-publishers-say-pandora-is-at-war-with-songwriters}}</ref><ref name=pk-royalties>{{cite web|last=Griffin|first=Jodie|title=Why Internet Radio Royalties Led Pandora to Buy an FM Radio Station|url=http://publicknowledge.org/blog/why-internet-radio-royalties-led-pandora-buy-|publisher=Public Knowledge|accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref> ASCAP also objected to the deal, filing a petition to deny with the FCC. The organization argued that the acquisition was not in the public interest because of Pandora's intent to use it as a \"bargaining chip\" for royalty payments. ASCAP also alleged that Pandora did not provide enough information about its ownership structure, failing to prove that less than 25% of the company was owned by foreign interests. On January 14, 2014, the FCC denied the acquisition until Pandora \"demonstrate[s] adequate support for its foreign ownership compliance certification.\"<ref name=billboard-fccshelved>{{cite web|title=FCC Shelves Pandora's Bid For South Dakota Radio Station|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-management/5869791/fcc-shelves-pandoras-bid-for-south-dakota-radio|work=Billboard.biz|accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name=theregister-ascapdeny>{{cite web|title=Music licensor seeks to block Pandora from running a radio station|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/07/29/ascap_seeks_to_block_pandora_radio_licenese/|work=The Register |accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref> The FCC relented in 2015 and allowed Pandora to acquire the station under the premise that whatever foreign ownership Pandora had was widely dispersed;<ref name=\"nyt-fcc-ruling\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/05/business/media/fcc-allows-pandora-to-buy-south-dakota-radio-station.html|title=F.C.C. Allows Pandora to Buy South Dakota Radio Station|first=Ben|last=Sisario|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2015-05-04|accessdate=2015-05-04}}</ref> Pandora ultimately sold the station to Houston Hargo, who owns and operates three other stations in South Dakota, two years after buying the station.<ref>https://radioinsight.com/category/headlines/sales/ June 19, 2017</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2013, Pandora removed the 40-hour-per-month limit on free mobile listening (originally announced on February 27, 2013). Pandora stated that it was able to make this change \"thanks to the rapid progress of its mobile advertising.\"<ref>[https://archive.is/20130905012109/http://investor.pandora.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=227956&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1849420 \"Pandora Removes 40-Hour-Per-Month Limit On Free Mobile Listening\"], Pandora.com, August 22, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Pandora signed an agreement with some music copyright owners for lower royalties in exchange for more frequent streaming of songs. Though not illegal, this practice raised comparisons to [[payola]], which is illegal payment for airplay on terrestrial radio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/11/26/366339553/pandoras-new-deal-different-pay-different-play|title=Pandora's New Deal: Different Pay, Different Play|date=November 26, 2014|work=NPR.org}}</ref>\n\nOn September 15, 2016, Pandora released \"Pandora Plus\", a new subscription service to compete with other streaming services; the price was set at $4.99 and was available in later months.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pandora-media-pandoraplus-idUSKCN11L1HZ |title=Pandora launches \"Pandora\" Plus replacing Pandora One |last= |first= |date=September 15, 2016 |website=[[reuters.com]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nIn May 2010, Pandora was named in [[Lead411]]'s 2010 Hottest [[San Francisco]] Companies list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lead411.com/san-francisco-companies.html |title=Lead411 launches \"Hottest Companies in San Francisco\" awards |publisher=Lead411.com |date=May 18, 2010 |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017093224/http://www.lead411.com/san-francisco-companies.html |archivedate=October 17, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' compared a number of music services and granted Pandora a \"B-\", writing, \"Free streaming radio, $36 a year for ad-free. Launched in 2005, Pandora is available on just about every platform. There's no on-demand, though, and stations tend to draw from a relatively small pool of albums.\"<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20663844,00.html |last= Anderson |first= Kyle |title= What's the Best Music Service? |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=January 18, 2013 |location=New York |publisher=Time Inc. |page=14}}</ref> As of March 2014, the annual option was eliminated, and the $3.99 monthly plan was the only way to get Pandora One. The price rose to $4.99 a month in July 2014. The annual subscription was brought back and is now $54.89 a year.\n\n== Advertising ==\nPandora initially offered a subscription-only service without commercials. However, the idea of paying did not sit well with most U.S. consumers and the company had to consider alternative business models to offer a free service. Then, in December 2005 Pandora sold its first advertisement.<ref name=\"Music Genome Project 2012\">\"Pandora Radio/Music Genome Project.\" Innovation Masters: History's Best Examples of Business Transformation. Ed. Miranda H. Ferrara and Michele P. LaMeau. Detroit: Gale, 2012. 267-270. Gale Virtual Reference Library. Web. June 10, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Pandora began playing more advertisements per hour in certain geographies and demographics. Pandora normally plays no more than 6 advertisements per hour for free users.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilking|first1=Rick|title=Yes, you're hearing more ads on Pandora these days|url=http://qz.com/463470/yes-youre-hearing-more-ads-on-pandora-these-days/|website=Quartz|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Revenue ===\nPandora became fairly popular within just two years. Starting from 2010 to 2012 Pandora's registered users had increased from 45 million to 125 million. The company's revenue increased from $55 million to $274 million, in which a majority of it from advertising. In order to appeal to a large audience of consumers, Pandora offers ad-free access for $36 a year.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/16/business/media/pandora-courts-local-advertisers-by-reaching-a-narrow-audience.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first1=Ben | last1=Sisario | first2=Tanzina | last2=Vega | title=Pandora Courts Local Advertisers by Reaching a Narrow Audience | date=April 15, 2012}}</ref> During its 2011 fiscal year, Pandora reported $138 million in revenue with a $1.8 million net loss, excluding the cost of a special dividend associated with the IPO.<ref>Pandora Media, Inc. \"[http://services.corporate-ir.net/SEC.Enhanced/SecCapsule.aspx?c=227956&fid=7621947 Prospectus, SEC Form S-1].\" June 14, 2011. Retrieved June 22, 2011.</ref> Overall, Pandora has a 78% of Internet radio, and it has a 9.3% share of the U.S. [[public radio]]. Finally, in 2013 industry-wide total radio ad revenue increased to $17.6 billion in the U.S.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-05-20/pandora-can-extend-lead-in-online-music-cfo-herring-says.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Anthony | last=Palazzo | title=Pandora Can Extend Lead in Online Music, CFO Herring Says | date=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Pitch to advertisers ===\nPandora obtains its advertisers by explaining that the company reaches a narrower audience compared to terrestrial radio. \"Pandora's pitch to advertisers is that its technology can cater to consumers with far greater precision than radio \u2013 it can pinpoint listeners by age and sex, ZIP code or even musical taste.\"<ref name=\"nytimes.com\" />\n\n=== Methods of advertising ===\nThere are a few different methods of advertising on Pandora. Audio advertising comes in spots of 15 to 30 seconds, and run once every 20 minutes. However, users only encounter ads if they are engaging with the site, like contributing a thumbs up or a thumbs down when changing a song or station.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/16/business/media/pandora-courts-local-advertisers-by-reaching-a-narrow-audience.html|title=Pandora Courts Local Advertisers by Reaching a Narrow Audience|first1=Ben|last1=Sisario|first2=Tanzina|last2=Vega|date=April 15, 2012|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\nNext, there are [[banner ads]] which are featured on the wallpaper of the site. As noted by ''[[the New York Times]]'', banner ads are on Pandora in order \"to promote engagement, audio segments can be accompanied by clickable display ads offering coupons or product information.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nAdvertising on Pandora works through a method of collecting [[data]] from the users online browsing activity. Once the [[data]] is collected, the company uses the data to show the user target ads. This process of advertising is also known as [[behavioral advertising]]. Pandora offers its users the option of submitting out of the targeted ads, by an opt-out configuration on its website. Opting-out will only prevent targeted ads, meaning users may continue to see generic (non-targeted ads) from these companies after they opt-out. Eventually, Pandora offers either targeted [[advertisements]] or generic advertisements for its non-subscribed users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pandora.com/advertising/preferences|title=Your Advertising Choices|publisher=}}</ref> However, Pandora's advertising does not offer local content such as the local news, weather, traffic, and talk.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\" />\n\n=== Market segments ===\nPandora has created two [[market segment]]s, one for Spanish listeners, and another for English listeners. By creating multiple market segments, Pandora's advertising is customized to its users' needs. In order to create the first two market segments, the company cross-referenced its registered user data with [[U.S. census]]. Then, the cross reference allows the company to identify zip codes with high populations of Hispanic and Spanish-speaking people, and finally it ran tests overlaying the two data sets to infer which listeners fit into those buckets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adage.com/article/digital/pandora-past-tracking-cookie-mining-user-data/245269/ |title=Pandora Looks Past the Tracking Cookie By Mining User Data|author=Tim Peterson |date=November 14, 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Internet radio stations]]\n* [[List of online music databases]]\n* [[List of streaming media systems]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/101/pandora.html Pandora featured in Fast Company]\n* [http://www.10zenmonkeys.com/2007/05/03/closing-pandoras-box-the-end-of-internet-radio/ Closing Pandora's Box: The End of Internet Radio?], May 3, 2007 interview with Tim Westergren\n* [http://news.cnet.com/8301-10784_3-9821318-7.html Pandora adds classical music]\n* [http://intruders.tv/en-tech/the-story-of-pandora-so-far-from-founder-tim-westergren/ Interview with Tim Westergren about the Music Genome Project and Pandora]\n* [http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/President-of-the-USA-Rocker-Challenges-Pandora-905442.htm Dave Dederer & nuTsie Challenge Pandora]\n* [http://www.inc.com/magazine/20071001/pandoras-long-strange-trip.html Inc. Magazine profile of Tim Westergren]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/08/technology/08pandora.html New York Times article on Tim Westergren and Pandora]\n* [https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2013/06/23/pink-floyd-royalties-pandora-column/2447445/ Pink Floyd: Pandora's Internet radio royalty ripoff] USA TODAY, 2013\n\n{{Music streaming services}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandora Radio}}\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Online music and lyrics databases]]\n[[Category:Internet radio in the United States]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:BlackBerry software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:Music streaming services]]\n[[Category:Windows Phone software]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Recommender systems]]\n[[Category:WatchOS software]]\n[[Category:2011 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:2019 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Sirius XM Satellite Radio]]\n[[Category:American corporate subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:American music websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Music streaming and recommendation website}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = Pandora\n| logo             = Pandora wordmark.svg\n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| location         = Oakland, California, U.S\n| locations        = 26\n| founder          = Will Glaser <br> [[Jon Kraft]]<br>[[Tim Westergren]]\n| services         = [[Internet radio]]\n| url              = {{URL|http://pandora.com}}\n| programming_language= [[Java (programming language)|Java]]\n| alexa            = {{decrease}} 634 (January 2019)<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web|url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/pandora.com |title= Pandora.com Site Info | publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n| advertising      = [[Banner ad]]s, video ads, audio ads\n| registration     = Optional (required to save stations)\n| language         = [[English language|English]]\n| native_clients   = [[Universal Windows Platform|Universal Windows App]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|2000|01}} (as Savage Beast Technologies)<br>[[Oakland, California]], U.S.\n| area_served      = United States\n| key_people       = Roger J. Lynch {{small|([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])}}<ref name=\":0\" /><br>Aim\u00e9e Lapic ([[Chief marketing officer|CMO]])<br>David Gerbitz ([[Chief operating officer|COO]])<br>Chris Phillips ([[Chief product officer|CPO]])\n| num_employees    = 2,200+\n| parent           = [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]]\n| subsidiaries     = [[Rdio]] (as of December 22, 2015), [[Next Big Sound]]\n| num_users        = 71.4 million active (2018),<ref name=PandoraPR02092017>https://finance.yahoo.com/news/pandora-reports-q2-2018-financial-200100666.html</ref> 6.0 million subscribers (2018)<ref name=PandoraPR02092017 />\n| current_status   = Active\n}}\n'''Pandora''' (also known as '''Pandora Media''' or '''Pandora Radio''') is an American [[Comparison of on-demand streaming music services|music streaming]] and automated [[Recommender system|music recommendation]] [[internet radio]] service powered by the [[Music Genome Project]] and headquartered in Oakland, California. The service, operated by [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]], is available in the United States.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|title=Pandora No Longer Available in Australia and New Zealand|url=http://help.pandora.com/customer/portal/articles/2830912|work=Pandora Customer Support|accessdate=July 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713235134/http://help.pandora.com/customer/portal/articles/2830912|archive-date=July 13, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The service plays songs that have similar musical traits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://computer.howstuffworks.com/internet/basics/pandora.htm|title=How Pandora Radio Works|last=Layton|first=Julia|date=|website=HowStuffWorks|access-date=July 23, 2017}}</ref> The user then provides positive or negative feedback (as [[thumbs up]] or [[thumbs down]]) for songs chosen by the service, and the feedback is taken into account in the subsequent selection of other songs to play. The service can be accessed either through a [[web browser]] or with its [[mobile app]]. Pandora is a [[freemium]] service; basic features are free with advertisements or limitations, while additional features, such as improved streaming quality, music downloads and offline channels are offered via paid subscriptions.\n\nIn 2014, Pandora had about 76 million monthly users, and about a 70% share of the internet radio market in the U.S.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://adage.com/article/media/u-s-review-rules-covering-pandora-songwriter-fees/293541/ | title=U.S. to Review Rules Covering Pandora Songwriter Fees | work=[[Advertising Age]] | date=June 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPandora's Promoted Stations rely on its core [[Music Genome Project]]. Overall, the Music Genome Project of more than 450 attributes assigned to each song with a human-curated database of recorded music.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.sfgate.com/technology/article/Pandora-advertisers-hope-to-turn-tunes-into-5470034.php | title=Pandora advertisers hope to turn tunes into dollars | work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] | first=Benny | last=Evangelista | date=May 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]] acquired Pandora for $3.5 billion in stock.<ref name=completes>{{cite news | url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/sirius-xm-completes-acquisition-of-pandora-1203125882/ | title=Sirius XM Completes Acquisition of Pandora | first=Jem | last=Aswad | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | date=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=wraps>{{cite news | url=https://www.bizjournals.com/newyork/news/2019/02/01/sirius-xm-wraps-up-pandora-acquisition.html | title=Sirius XM wraps up Pandora acquisition | first=Anthony | last=Noto | work=[[American City Business Journals]] | date=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Pandora Logo RGB thumbnail new large.png|thumb|upright=0.65|App logo of Pandora]]\nIn 2000, Will Glaser, [[Jon Kraft]] and [[Tim Westergren]] founded the company as Savage Beast Technologies.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/on-small-business/when-we-were-small-pandora/2015/02/06/11ad75f4-ad5c-11e4-9c91-e9d2f9fde644_story.html | title=When we were small: Pandora | last=Harrison | first=J. D. | work=[[The Washington Post]] | date=February 6, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.inc.com/magazine/20071001/pandoras-long-strange-trip_pagen_2.html | title=Pandora's Long Strange Trip | first=Stephanie | last=Clifford | work=[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]] | date=October 1, 2007}}</ref> The idea was to create a radio station for each user, with music that the user prefers and without music that they do not prefer. The company ran through its initial $2 million in funding by 2001. Founder [[Tim Westergren]] then convinced Pandora's 50 employees to work for two years without pay.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://thehustle.co/pandora-speech | title=How Pandora\u2019s Founder Convinced 50 Early Employees to Work 2 Years Without Pay | first=Sam | last=Parr | work=The Hustle | date=May 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nInitially, the company pursued a transitional strategy of licensing technology to companies such as [[AOL]], [[Best Buy]], [[Barnes & Noble]], and [[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]]. In July 2005, the company changed its name to Pandora Media.<ref name=:2>{{cite news | url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1230276/000119312511087171/ds1a.htm | title=PANDORA MEDIA, INC. Amendment No. 2 to FORM S-1 | publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]]}}</ref>\n\nThe website began as a paid service but quickly changed to an advertiser-sponsored service to make it also available free for users.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://techcrunch.com/2005/11/10/pandora-now-offers-free-option/ | title=https://techcrunch.com/2005/11/10/pandora-now-offers-free-option/ | publisher=[[TechCrunch]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the company went [[public company|public]] via an [[initial public offering]] on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref>[https://techcrunch.com/2011/06/24/in-the-war-over-tech-ipos-the-new-york-stock-exchange-is-drawing-some-blood/ In The War Over Tech IPOs, The New York Stock Exchange Is Drawing Some Blood] June 24, 2011</ref>\n\nOn March 7, 2013, Pandora chairman and [[chief executive officer]] Joseph J. Kennedy announced that he would leave the company after nine years.<ref>{{Cite news | url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/07/chief-executive-at-pandora-media-to-step-down/ | title=Chief Executive at Pandora Media to Step Down | last=Sisario | first=Ben| work=[[The New York Times]] | date=March 7, 2013 | url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2013, Pandora announced that its radio streaming service had 200 million users, including 70 million [[monthly active users]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2013/04/09/pandora-hits-200-million-registered-users-in-the-us-nearly-1-5-billion-monthly-listener-hours/ | title=Pandora hits 200 million registered users in the US, 1.5 billion monthly listener hours | last=Wauters | first=Robin | work=[[The Next Web]] | date=April 9, 2013}}</ref> By December 2013, Pandora accounted for 70% of all [[Internet radio]] listening in the United States.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nOn September 1, 2013, Pandora removed a 40-hour-per-month limitation for free mobile listening.<ref name=\"thenextweb1\">{{cite news | url=https://thenextweb.com/insider/2013/08/22/pandora-will-remove-its-40-hour-per-month-mobile-listening-cap-on-september-1st/ | title=Pandora will remove its 40 hour per month mobile listening cap on September 1st | work=[[The Next Web]] | date=August 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2015, Pandora removed lyrics from song pages but returned them by July. On April 16, 2015, song samples were removed. At around the same time, a new feature was introduced to give users the ability to receive notices about their favorite artists through the music player. They also redesigned the thumbs up/down feature to allow the listener to undo their action.\n\nBy January 2015, songs played on Pandora had received more than 50 billion thumbs up from users.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://blog.pandora.com/2015/01/29/50-billion-thumbs-3/ | title=50 Billion Thumbs | first=Nicole | last=McInnes | work=Pandora | date=January 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2017, Pandora revealed that 56 million of its 81 million active users subscribe to the ''Today's Country'' station and that [[country music]] accounted for more than 1.7 billion listening hours on the platform in 2016.<ref>[https://www.theverge.com/2017/4/27/15451070/pandora-country-music-streaming Can country music save Pandora?] [[The Verge]] Retrieved March 15, 2018</ref>\n\nOn July 31, 2017, Pandora discontinued services in Australia and New Zealand, citing a need to focus solely on the U.S. market.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.news.com.au/technology/home-entertainment/audio/pandora-no-longer-available-in-australia-and-new-zealand-heres-what-you-need-to-know/news-story/4d2eddd01342d4dfa2cd7319cb3bf7bf | title=Pandora to leave Australia: Here\u2019s what you need to know | work=[[news.com.au]] | date=July 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7849103/pandora-leaving-australia-new-zealand-markets | title=Pandora Is Winding Down Operations in Australia and New Zealand | first=Marc | last=Schneider | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Roger Lynch became CEO and stated that he wanted to expand the service's focus on [[podcast]]s, with similar discovery features to those for music, as well as new monetization options.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://variety.com/2018/digital/news/pandora-podcast-genome-project-1202661263/ | title=Pandora CEO Roger Lynch Wants to Create the Podcast Genome Project | last=Roettgers | first=Janko | work=Variety | date=January 11, 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, Lynch's departure was announced following the approval of Sirius XM's acquisition of Pandora. Lynch will be replaced by Sirius XM CEO Jim Meyer.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pandora-ceo-roger-lynch-exits-786283/ | title=Pandora\u2019s CEO Roger Lynch Exits As SiriusXM Takes Over | last=Wang | first=Amy X. | last2=Wang | first2=Amy X. | work=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=January 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 15, 2019, Pandora announced the launch of its own in-app voice assistant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/01/15/pandora-launches-a-personalized-voice-assistant-on-ios-and-android/|title=Pandora launches a personalized voice assistant on iOS and Android|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-17}}</ref>\n\nOn February 26, 2019, Pandora announced the launch of Pandora Stories, a new marketing tool for artists. The feature allows artists to build music playlists combined with voice tracks, where they can add a narrative and deeper insights.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/02/26/pandora-stories-launches-combining-music-and-podcasting-in-a-new-format/|title=Pandora Stories launches, combining music and podcasting in a new format|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-27}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, Pandora's parent company, Sirius XM, signed a multiyear deal with Marvel to launch a series of superhero-based podcasts in 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/10/22/772355077/marvel-expands-its-universe-to-superhero-podcasts-on-siriusxm-and-pandora|title=It's Superhero Time On Podcasts: Star-Lord And Black Widow To Step Up To The Mic|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisitions ===\nOn June 11, 2013, Pandora announced it would purchase FM radio station [[KXMZ]] in [[Rapid City, South Dakota]].<ref name=\"verge-pandorafm\">{{cite web|title=Pandora buys FM radio station in a wily move to fight music labels|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/6/11/4420936/pandora-buys-fm-radio-station-in-a-wily-move-to-fight-music-companies|work=The Verge|accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"hills-pandora\">{{cite web|last=Harrison|first=Christopher|title=Why Pandora bought an FM radio station|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/technology/304763-why-pandora-bought-an-fm-radio-station|date=June 11, 2013}}</ref> On October 7, 2015, Pandora announced it had acquired independent ticketing agency [[Ticketfly]] for $450 million.<ref name=\"ticketfly\">{{cite web|title=Game changer: Pandora confirms $450m acquisition of Ticketfly|url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/game-changer-pandora-confirms-450m-acquisition-ticketfly/|work=musicbusinessworldwide|accessdate=December 30, 2015|date=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, streaming music service [[Rdio]], founded by Skype co-founders [[Janus Friis]] and [[Niklas Zennstroem]], declared bankruptcy and sold its assets to Pandora for $75 million.<ref>By James Risley, GeekWire. \"[http://www.geekwire.com/2015/rdio-to-shut-down-streaming-music-service-sells-assets-to-pandora-for-75m/ Rdio to shut down streaming music service, sells assets to Pandora for $75M].\" November 16, 2015. November 17, 2015.</ref> Pandora retained 100 Rdio employees, including Iain Morris and Rich Masio, who joined a growing licensing department in pursuit of direct licenses with labels and publishers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.musicbusinessworldwide.com/can-these-former-rdio-execs-woo-the-music-biz-for-pandora/|title=Can these former Rdio execs woo the music biz for Pandora? - Music Business Worldwide|date=January 25, 2016 |newspaper=Music Business Worldwide|language=en-US |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Pandora announced it would acquire digital audio [[List of advertising technology companies|ad technology firm]] [[AdsWizz]] for $145 million.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/21/pandora-doubles-down-on-ad-tech-with-acquisition-of-adswizz-for-145-million/ | title=Pandora doubles down on ad tech with acquisition of AdsWizz for $145 million | first=Sarah | last=Perez | work=[[TechCrunch]] | date=March 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio]] acquired Pandora for $3.5 billion in stock.<ref name=completes/><ref name=wraps/>\n\n== Features ==\n\n=== Streaming ===\n{{More citations needed|section|date=October 2017}}\nThe service has two subscription plans: a free subscription supported by advertisements, and a fee-based subscription without advertisements.<ref name=\":1\" /> Listeners can tune into established [[Music genre|genre]] stations, other users' stations or create their own stations based on their musical interests.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifewire.com/pandora-internet-music-streaming-1847453|title=Guide to Pandora Internet Music Streaming|work=Lifewire|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref> Each track played can be responded to with favorable (thumbs up) or unfavorable (thumbs down) buttons, which determine if it and similar songs should be played in the station.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifewire.com/how-pandora-creates-stations-1847393|title=Learn How Pandora Creates Stations and How You Can Customize Them|work=Lifewire|access-date=2018-12-03|language=en}}</ref> A second thumbs down to the same artist will ban that artist from the selected station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techwalla.com/articles/how-to-ban-an-artist-from-one-of-your-stations-on-pandoracom|title=How to Ban an Artist From One of Your Stations on Pandora.com|website=Techwalla}}</ref> A thumbs down immediately skips a song, but the number of times a user can skip tracks is limited unless they are using one of the paid subscription plans.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lifewire.com/customizing-your-pandora-stations-1847412|title=Hidden Secrets of Customizing Your Pandora Stations|work=Lifewire|access-date=2018-12-03|language=en}}</ref> The free version of Pandora also plays short advertisements between every three or four songs.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThere is a setting in each member's account allowing the user to censor songs with explicit lyrics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/block-explicit-lyrics-in-music-subscription-services/|title=How to block explicit lyrics in streaming music|last=Broida|first=Rick|date=2018-05-23|work=CNET|access-date=2018-12-03|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile listening, users are offered the ability to buy the songs or albums at various online retailers like iTunes or Amazon.<ref name=\":1\" /> More than 450 musical attributes are considered when selecting the next song.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/3/28/17172954/pandora-personalized-playlists-automatically-generate|title=Pandora launches automatically generated personalized playlists|work=The Verge|access-date=2018-11-27}}</ref> These 450 attributes are combined into larger groups called focus traits, of which there are 2,000.<ref name=\":4\">{{Citation|last=Miller|first=Michael|title=Playing Music on Pandora|date=2015-06-01|url=http://www.informit.com/articles/article.aspx?p=2337783|access-date=2018-12-03}}</ref> Examples of these are rhythm [[syncopation]], key [[tonality]], and vocal [[harmonies]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nIn October 2014, less than 5 percent of active listeners were paying subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/2592715-pandora-medias-p-ceo-brian-mcandrews-on-q3-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript?part=single |title=Pandora Media's (P) CEO Brian McAndrews on Q3 2014 Results \u2013 Earnings Call Transcript |publisher=[[Seeking Alpha]] |date=October 24, 2014}}</ref> At the time of Pandora's [[Initial Public Offering|IPO]] in 2011, Pandora had 800,000 tracks from 80,000 artists in its library and 80 million users.<ref>{{cite web|title=With 80 Million Users, Pandora Files To Go Public |url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/02/11/pandora-files-to-go-public/ |publisher=[[TechCrunch]] |date=February 11, 2011}}</ref> By November 2014, Pandora had approximately doubled its library size, topping 1.5 million songs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2014/11/26/366339553/pandoras-new-deal-different-pay-different-play |title=Pandora's New Deal: Different Pay, Different Play |first=Laura |last=Sydell |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=November 26, 2014 |accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> As of end of mid-year 2018, Pandora had 71.4 million active users.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/pandora-reports-q2-2018-financial-200100666.html|title=Pandora Reports Q2 2018 Financial Results|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Pandora announced additional features and subscription options, including a mid-level subscription service known as ''Pandora Plus'' that offers advertisement-free streaming, offline playback support using a prediction mechanism and more skips and replays. Users of the free service were also provided more skips and replays in exchange for watching an advertisement. Pandora also announced the launch of an on-demand service similar to competitors such as [[Apple Music]] and [[Spotify]].<ref name=\"engadget-newplans\">{{cite web|title=Pandora relaunches its mid-level $5 monthly subscription tier [Updated]|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/09/15/pandora-relaunches-its-mid-level-5-monthly-subscription-tier/|website=Engadget|publisher=AOL |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/pandora-launches-song-replays-more-skips-for-all/ |title=Pandora launches song replays, more skips for all |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, 2017, Pandora launched ''Pandora Premium'', a new service allowing users to listen to and create playlists of individual songs on demand. Pandora's suggestions engine suggests and recommends songs and albums, as well as generates playlists based on similar songs. Pandora also emphasized a use of machine learning and manual curation, and that it had filtered \"karaoke tracks, knock-off covers and pet sounds (but not ''[[Pet Sounds]]'') that slow down other services\" from its library.<ref name=\"tc-premium\">{{cite web|title=Pandora\u2019s on-demand music service finally arrives|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/13/pandoras-on-demand-music-service-finally-arrives/|website=TechCrunch |publisher=AOL |accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Limitations ===\nTo comply with the requirements and protections offered by the [[DMCA]], Pandora serves users only in the United States, using [[IP addresses]] to block users from non-complying countries.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Breaking Pandora's Heart...|url = http://blog.pandora.com/2007/05/03/breaking_pandor/|website = Pandora Blog |accessdate=September 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nInitially, users with free accounts could listen to 40 hours of music a month, and could pay $0.99 per month for unlimited streaming. In September 2011, Pandora removed the 40-hour listening limit.<ref name=\"NewPandora\">[http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2011/09/new-pandora-for.html \"New Pandora for All\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110923190211/http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2011/09/new-pandora-for.html |date=September 23, 2011 }}. Pandora Blog. September 22, 2011. Retrieved September 3, 2011.</ref> This 40-hour limit on free listening was re-introduced in March 2013 for mobile devices.<ref>[http://gigaom.com/2013/02/28/pandora-caps-monthly-free-tunes-on-mobiles-to-40-hours/ Pandora caps monthly free tunes on mobiles to 40 hours \u2014 Tech News and Analysis]. Gigaom.com (February 28, 2013). Retrieved January 17, 2014.</ref> However, this limit was removed once more in September of the same year.<ref name=\"thenextweb1\" />\n\nIn September 2016, a rewind function was introduced allowing users to replay a song. The updated streaming service also allowed users to skip an unidentified number of additional songs per hour if they opted to watch an ad. Previous to that, users were only able to skip six songs in an hour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/pandora-launches-song-replays-more-skips-for-all/|title=Pandora launches song replays, more skips for all|last=Solsman|first=Joan E.|website=CNET|language=en|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Mobile devices ===\n[[File:Pandora-on-iOS.png|thumb|Pandora [[iOS]] App|318x318px]]\nPandora is available on [[iOS]] devices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/pandora-radio/id284035177|title=Pandora Music on the App Store|website=App Store}}</ref> It is ad-supported and retains the original skip limits. Pandora is also available on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] (for tablets and mobile phones),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.pandora.android&hl=en|title=Pandora Music|first=|last=Pandora|date=November 19, 2017|publisher=|via=Google Play}}</ref> and [[BlackBerry 10]] handsets via the Amazon app store.\n\nThe Pandora for [[BlackBerry OS]] (7.1 and earlier) application is limited to AT&T, Sprint, Verizon, T-Mobile, Boost Mobile, and U.S. Cellular carriers, but by visiting the Pandora website directly other BlackBerry users have been successful in downloading and using the application.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.softandapp.com/pandora.html|title=Pandora Radio - Free Download & App Review|website=www.softandapp.com|language=en|access-date=2017-12-06}}</ref>\n\n== Technical information ==\nThe Pandora media player is based on [[OpenLaszlo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.openlaszlo.org/showcase#Pandora |title=Showcase |publisher=OpenLaszlo |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024043132/http://openlaszlo.org/showcase#Pandora |archivedate=October 24, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Pandora can also be accessed through many [[digital media receiver|media streaming devices]] such as [[Roku]], Reciva-based radios (from companies like [[Grace Digital]], [[Sanyo]], and [[Sangean]]), Frontier Silicon-based connected audio systems, [[Slim Devices]], [[Sonos]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonos.com/get_music/radio_services/pandora/ |title=Sonos Multi-Room Music System |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080421124104/http://www.sonos.com/get_music/radio_services/pandora/ |archivedate=April 21, 2008}}</ref> and [[HEOS by Denon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.denon.com/us/heos |title=HEOS by Denon Wireless Speakers}}</ref> product(s). On July 11, 2008, Pandora launched a mobile version of their software for the [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] [[iPhone]] and [[iPod Touch]] through the [[iTunes App Store]]. Pandora is also available for [[Windows Phone]], [[Windows 10]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] phones,<ref>[http://www.pandora.com/android Pandora Radio is now available to stream music on your Android phone]. Retrieved September 17, 2009.</ref> [[BlackBerry]] platforms, HP [[webOS]] (used on the [[Palm Pre]], [[Palm Pixi]], [[Palm Pre 2]], and [[HP Veer]]) {{Citation needed|date=October 2018}}. Pandora was the provider for [[MSN]] Radio until MSN discontinued their internet radio service on June 18, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msrplans.com/MSN_Drops_Pandora.html |title=Free online radio removed from MSN |publisher=Msrplans.com |date=June 19, 2008 |accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> A modified version of Pandora has been made available for [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]]. Pandora is available on [[Comcast]]'s X1/X2 cable TV products. A GNU/Linux-based application, called Pithos, which is available for accessing Pandora Radio, is available for most distributions via their repositories and is also available to build from source. SoundSpectrum's iOS-based visualizing application Tunr<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.soundspectrum.com/tunr/|title=Tunr - All-in-One Visual Music Player by SoundSpectrum|website=www.soundspectrum.com|language=en-US |accessdate=March 4, 2017}}</ref> has native support for Pandora, but requires a subscription.\n\nWith a subscription to Pandora's One service, Windows and Mac users can download a desktop application for Pandora that uses the [[Adobe Air]] without using a web browser to access Pandora. All the normal functionality is included such as thumbs up/down, skip, pause and access to all channels on a user's account.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://lifehacker.com/396393/top-10-apps-worth-installing-adobe-air-for|title=Top 10 Apps Worth Installing Adobe AIR For|last=Purdy|first=Kevin|work=Lifehacker|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Business model ==\nPandora decided to be a consumer-oriented music discovery service, specifically a non-interactive radio station.  In the three months that ended October 31, 2011, advertising comprised 88% of Pandora's total revenues;<ref name=\"sec.gov\">Pandora Media, Inc. \"[https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1230276/000119312511323367/d244588d10q.htm 2011 3rd Quarter Report, SEC Form 10-Q].\" November 29, 2011. Retrieved December 2, 2011.</ref> that was reported as 80% in December 2013.<ref name=\":0\" />  RPM (revenue per 1000s of hours) is determined based on CPMs (cost per thousand impressions). CPMs are largely dependent upon network effects and thus increase as a website scales and adds users. As such, Pandora's strategy in order to allow for widespread distribution was to offer a service unbundled from devices and transport. Pandora also works with system-on-chip manufacturers to embed its technologies on the chips they sell to consumer electronics manufacturers like [[Panasonic]], [[Samsung]], and [[Sony]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2010/10/an-update-on-pa.html/ | title=An Update on Pandora in Your Living Room | accessdate=December 2, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128225153/http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2010/10/an-update-on-pa.html | archivedate=November 28, 2011 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nPandora's cost structure is highly variable, with content acquisition costs representing roughly 50% of total costs.<ref name=\"sec.gov\" /> There are three main costs associated with content acquisition. First, [[SoundExchange]] collects content fees on behalf of labels or artists on the recording themselves. These are by far the largest content acquisition costs.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}} Second, Pandora pays licensing fees to agencies such as [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]], [[ASCAP]], or [[SESAC]] in order to compensate composers, songwriters and publishers. Lastly, Pandora also pays [[TiVo Corporation]] for song and artist information; this has recently been structured as a flat monthly fee.\n\nHigh variable costs mean that Pandora does not have significant [[operating leverage]], and in the next couple years might actually have negative operating leverage due to an unfavorable shift in product mix towards mobile. Pandora is currently estimated to monetize mobile hours at roughly one-ninth the rate of desktop hours.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-11/pandora-slow-to-lure-mobile-ad-dollars-even-as-ipad-listeners-flock-tech.html/ | title=Pandora Slow to Lure Mobile-Ad Dollars Even as Users Flock | accessdate=December 2, 2011 | work=Bloomberg | first1=Andy | last1=Fixmer | first2=Ari | last2=Levy | date=October 11, 2011}}</ref> Since Pandora pays the same licensing cost per hour irrespective of the user's platform, the net contribution to earnings per mobile hour is even more skewed with respect to contribution to earnings from desktop hours. Mobile revenues will improve over time as Pandora shifts from relying on third-party ad networks to selling ad inventory internally at premium rates.\n\nIn January 2011, Pandora met with [[investment bank]]s to consider a possible $100 million IPO.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN1310587520110113 | work=Reuters | first=Clare | last=Baldwin | title=UPDATE 1-Groupon, Pandora met this week with IPO bankers | date=January 13, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jay | last=Yarow  |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/pandora-was-saved-by-the-iphone-now-its-thinking-ipo-2010-3 |title=Pandora Was Saved By The iPhone, Now It's Thinking IPO |publisher=[[Business Insider]] |date=March 8, 2010 |accessdate=November 6, 2012}}</ref> The company filed with the SEC for a $100mm IPO on February 11, 2011 and officially began trading on the [[New York Stock Exchange]] with ticker symbol \"P\" on June 15, 2011 at a price of $16/share. This gave them a valuation of nearly $2.6 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cabot.net/News/2011/06/Pandora-IPO.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110731155546/http://www.cabot.net/News/2011/06/Pandora-IPO.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 31, 2011 |title=Internet Radio Company Pandora Sets IPO |publisher=[[Cabot Investing Advice]] |date=June 15, 2011 |accessdate=November 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nPandora announced $80.8 million in total revenue for their first quarter of fiscal 2012, which was up 58% over their previous year Q1 results. Of the $80.8 million, $70.6 million came from advertising, while the other $10.2 million came from subscription. In addition, Pandora has seen a 62% advertising revenue increase, and a 38% subscription revenue increase year-over-year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/05/23/pandoras-quarterly-results-80-8m-in-revenue-52m-active-users-3-09b-listening-hours-per-month/|title=Pandora\u2019s Quarterly Results: $80.8M In Revenue, 52M Active Users & 3.09B Listening Hours|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2018-10-17|language=en-US}}</ref> However, the vast majority of Pandora's users remain on the free, ad-supported model.\n\n== Royalties ==\nBecause of [[Internet Radio Day of Silence|the passage of DMCA in 1998]] that increased fees and asked for licensing guarantees, the Pandora service was only available in Australia, New Zealand and the [[United States]],<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Breaking Pandora's Heart...\n| url = http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2007/05/breaking_pandor.html\n| publisher = Pandora Blog\n| date = May 3, 2007\n| accessdate = May 7, 2007\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| title = Canada\n| url = http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2007/05/canada.html\n| publisher = Pandora Blog\n| date = May 14, 2007\n| accessdate = May 15, 2007\n }}</ref> until service to Australia and New Zealand ceased on 1 August 2017 after \"consideration of external factors\".<ref name=\":3\" />  These rulings affect all U.S.-based Internet-based radio stations (terrestrial radio is not affected).\n\nAs of July 2008, Pandora was in talks with major music labels regarding royalty issues to allow a return to the European market.\nCosts remain a concern because of European royalty standards and a low demand for paid music services.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Pandora UK closes after royalties demands\n| url = https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/01/08/pandora_uk_closes/\n| publisher = The Register\n| date = January 8, 2008\n| accessdate = January 8, 2008\n }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the founder of Pandora stated that the company may be on the verge of collapse. Royalty fees account for a majority portion of Pandora's revenues. If an agreement between Pandora and [[SoundExchange]] had not been reached, it could have meant the end of Pandora. \"We're losing money as it is,\" said [[Tim Westergren]]. \"The moment we think this problem in Washington is not going to get solved, we have to pull the plug because all we're doing is wasting money.\"<ref>Peter Whoriskey,[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/15/AR2008081503367.html?hpid=topnews \"Giant of Internet Radio Nears Its 'Last Stand'\"], The Washington Post, August 16, 2008</ref>\n\nOn September 30, 2008, a bill was passed by the U.S. House and Senate to allow sites like Pandora to continue negotiations with SoundExchange into 2009.\n\nOn July 7, 2009, Pandora announced that an agreement had been reached regarding the royalty issue, which would significantly reduce the royalty rate, making it possible for Pandora to stay in business. Also announced was that free listening would be limited to 40 hours per month, but can be extended to unlimited for that month for [[United States dollar|USD]]$0.99. \"The revised royalties are quite high,\" the company's blog notes, \"higher in fact than any other form of radio\".<ref>{{cite web|date=July 7, 2009 |url=http://blog.pandora.com/pandora/archives/2009/07/important_updat_1.html |title=Pandora: Important update on royalties |publisher=Blog.pandora.com |accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> The extended listening fee differs from \"upgrading\", which also disables advertisements, increases the bitrate from 64 to 192 [[Kbp/s|kbps]], and provides a dedicated music player (as opposed to listening through browser). This service, known as \"Pandora One\", costs $36 and is billed annually.<ref>[http://www.pandora.com/#/account/upgrade/ Unlimited ad-free listening for $36 per year], pandora.com. Retrieved September 17, 2009.</ref> Pandora has since introduced an option to purchase Pandora One subscriptions on a monthly basis at a rate of $3.99 per month.<ref>[http://help.pandora.com/customer/portal/articles/84834-pandora-one Pandora One Cost], pandora.com</ref> Also, in September 2013, Pandora began working with [[HitBliss]] to make Pandora One subscriptions available for HitBliss earned-payment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitbliss.com/pandora.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915051721/http://www.hitbliss.com/pandora.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 15, 2013 |title=Pandora One Subscriptions via |publisher=Hitbliss.com |accessdate=April 8, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nWith an update to the Pandora player in September 2011, the 40 hour cap was extended to 320 hours.<ref name=\"NewPandora\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://mashable.com/2011/09/21/pandora-redesign/ | title=Pandora Unleashes Redesigned Music Player With No Listening Cap | accessdate=September 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn November 22, 2011, Pandora reported its Q3 earnings. Royalty costs accounted for 50% of revenue, slightly better than expected. Its revenue, most of it from advertising, continues to rise at respectable rates. Not only has Pandora attracted more users but the average number of hours per user have also increased. Pandora now accounts for an estimated 4% of total US listening hours. As Pandora grows, it hopes to gain leverage on music labels and drive royalty costs down.<ref>Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry and Henry Blodget, [http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-11-23/research/30432348_1_pandora-higher-revenue-spotify \"Pandora Still Growing Like Gangbusters -- Now 4% Of Total US Radio Listening\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121010144/http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-11-23/research/30432348_1_pandora-higher-revenue-spotify |date=January 21, 2012 }}, Business Insider, November 23, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn December 9, 2011, the CEO of [[Spotify]], [[Daniel Ek]], announced Spotify Radio would offer an unlimited number of stations and unlimited skips. Though Pandora's usage is 70% mobile, the Spotify Radio app competes against Pandora's mobile market.<ref>Henry Blodget and Pascal-Emmanuel Gobry,[http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-12-09/tech/30493388_1_pandora-radio-service-radio-market \"Spotify Announces 'Spotify Radio' -- Presumably A Pandora-Killer\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211015122/http://articles.businessinsider.com/2011-12-09/tech/30493388_1_pandora-radio-service-radio-market |date=December 11, 2011 }}, Business Insider, December 9, 2011</ref>\n\nPandora CEO Tim Westergren has supported The Internet Radio Fairness Act or IRFA (H.R. 6480/S. 3609), which would reduce the company's royalty payments to the performers by 80 percent.<ref>{{cite web|last=Orlowski |first=Andrew |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/17/pandora_fairness/ |title=Pandora boss urges 85% pay cut for musicians. |publisher=Theregister.co.uk |date=October 17, 2012 |accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn November 5, 2012, Pandora filed suit in federal district court against [[ASCAP]] over royalty fees.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/11/5/3606252/pandora-ascap-lawsuit-licensing-fees | title=Pandora sues ASCAP over songwriter fees, asks court to establish 'reasonable' licensing | date=November 5, 2012 | accessdate=November 6, 2012}}</ref> In the suit, the company sought to advocate for lower licensing fees on all the songs represented by the ASCAP's 435,000 members.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-11-05/pandora-media-sues-ascap-seeking-lower-songwriter-fees.html | title=Pandora sues ASCAP Seeking Lower Songwriter Fees | date=November 5, 2012 | accessdate=December 5, 2012 | work=Bloomberg}}</ref>  On February 27, 2013, Pandora announced a 40-hour-per-month limit on free mobile listening. Pandora CEO Tim Westergren cited escalating royalty costs as the reason for the mobile cap.<ref>Tim Westergren, [http://blog.pandora.com/2013/02/27/a-note-to-our-listeners/ \"A note to our listeners\"], Pandora.com, February 27, 2013</ref>\n\nIn a ruling made public in March 2014, US District Judge Denise Cote ruled that Pandora's rate paid to ASCAP should remain the same, 1.85%. She cited (p.&nbsp;97) \"troubling coordination\" between two of the biggest publishing companies (Sony and UMPG) and ASCAP that alludes to core antitrust concern in the industry.<ref>UNITED STATES OF AMERICA, Plaintiff, v. AMERICAN SOCIETY OF COMPOSERS, AUTHORS, AND PUBLISHERS, Defendant. 97. United States District Court, Southern District of New York. March 18, 2014. Title 17: The S(c)ite For Copyright Law. Paul Fakler, March 19, 2014. Web. November 23, 2014.</ref>\n\nAfter arguing that both ASCAP and BMI were showing bias towards international broadcasters who own terrestrial radio stations, Pandora announced on June 11, 2013 that it would attempt to acquire [[KXMZ]], a radio station in South Dakota, under the presumption that doing so would allow it to access the same preferential licensing terms offered to services such as [[iHeartRadio]] (which is owned by [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]], itself America's largest radio broadcaster).<ref name=verge-pandorafm /><ref name=\"hills-pandora\" /> The move was criticized by David Israelite, CEO of the [[National Music Publishers Association]], who declared that Pandora was now \"at war with songwriters,\" and had lost its credibility because it was resorting to \"lawsuits and gimmicks\" to make its point. However, a member of [[Public Knowledge]] praised the move, by stating that it was \"a perfect example of the twisted incentives and strange results we get from a music licensing system that is based on who wants a license instead of just what they want to do with the music they\u2019re using.\"<ref name=verge-pandorapublisher>{{cite web|title=CEO of top music publishers' trade group says Pandora is at war with songwriters|work=The Verge|accessdate=June 13, 2013|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/6/12/4424796/music-publishers-say-pandora-is-at-war-with-songwriters}}</ref><ref name=pk-royalties>{{cite web|last=Griffin|first=Jodie|title=Why Internet Radio Royalties Led Pandora to Buy an FM Radio Station|url=http://publicknowledge.org/blog/why-internet-radio-royalties-led-pandora-buy-|publisher=Public Knowledge|accessdate=June 14, 2013}}</ref> ASCAP also objected to the deal, filing a petition to deny with the FCC. The organization argued that the acquisition was not in the public interest because of Pandora's intent to use it as a \"bargaining chip\" for royalty payments. ASCAP also alleged that Pandora did not provide enough information about its ownership structure, failing to prove that less than 25% of the company was owned by foreign interests. On January 14, 2014, the FCC denied the acquisition until Pandora \"demonstrate[s] adequate support for its foreign ownership compliance certification.\"<ref name=billboard-fccshelved>{{cite web|title=FCC Shelves Pandora's Bid For South Dakota Radio Station|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-management/5869791/fcc-shelves-pandoras-bid-for-south-dakota-radio|work=Billboard.biz|accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref><ref name=theregister-ascapdeny>{{cite web|title=Music licensor seeks to block Pandora from running a radio station|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/07/29/ascap_seeks_to_block_pandora_radio_licenese/|work=The Register |accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref> The FCC relented in 2015 and allowed Pandora to acquire the station under the premise that whatever foreign ownership Pandora had was widely dispersed;<ref name=\"nyt-fcc-ruling\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/05/business/media/fcc-allows-pandora-to-buy-south-dakota-radio-station.html|title=F.C.C. Allows Pandora to Buy South Dakota Radio Station|first=Ben|last=Sisario|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2015-05-04|accessdate=2015-05-04}}</ref> Pandora ultimately sold the station to Houston Hargo, who owns and operates three other stations in South Dakota, two years after buying the station.<ref>https://radioinsight.com/category/headlines/sales/ June 19, 2017</ref>\n\nOn September 1, 2013, Pandora removed the 40-hour-per-month limit on free mobile listening (originally announced on February 27, 2013). Pandora stated that it was able to make this change \"thanks to the rapid progress of its mobile advertising.\"<ref>[https://archive.is/20130905012109/http://investor.pandora.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=227956&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1849420 \"Pandora Removes 40-Hour-Per-Month Limit On Free Mobile Listening\"], Pandora.com, August 22, 2013</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Pandora signed an agreement with some music copyright owners for lower royalties in exchange for more frequent streaming of songs. Though not illegal, this practice raised comparisons to [[payola]], which is illegal payment for airplay on terrestrial radio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2014/11/26/366339553/pandoras-new-deal-different-pay-different-play|title=Pandora's New Deal: Different Pay, Different Play|date=November 26, 2014|work=NPR.org}}</ref>\n\nOn September 15, 2016, Pandora released \"Pandora Plus\", a new subscription service to compete with other streaming services; the price was set at $4.99 and was available in later months.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pandora-media-pandoraplus-idUSKCN11L1HZ |title=Pandora launches \"Pandora\" Plus replacing Pandora One |last= |first= |date=September 15, 2016 |website=[[reuters.com]] |accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nIn May 2010, Pandora was named in [[Lead411]]'s 2010 Hottest [[San Francisco]] Companies list.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lead411.com/san-francisco-companies.html |title=Lead411 launches \"Hottest Companies in San Francisco\" awards |publisher=Lead411.com |date=May 18, 2010 |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017093224/http://www.lead411.com/san-francisco-companies.html |archivedate=October 17, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2013, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' compared a number of music services and granted Pandora a \"B-\", writing, \"Free streaming radio, $36 a year for ad-free. Launched in 2005, Pandora is available on just about every platform. There's no on-demand, though, and stations tend to draw from a relatively small pool of albums.\"<ref>{{cite journal | url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20663844,00.html |last= Anderson |first= Kyle |title= What's the Best Music Service? |journal=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=January 18, 2013 |location=New York |publisher=Time Inc. |page=14}}</ref> As of March 2014, the annual option was eliminated, and the $3.99 monthly plan was the only way to get Pandora One. The price rose to $4.99 a month in July 2014. The annual subscription was brought back and is now $54.89 a year.\n\n== Advertising ==\nPandora initially offered a subscription-only service without commercials. However, the idea of paying did not sit well with most U.S. consumers and the company had to consider alternative business models to offer a free service. Then, in December 2005 Pandora sold its first advertisement.<ref name=\"Music Genome Project 2012\">\"Pandora Radio/Music Genome Project.\" Innovation Masters: History's Best Examples of Business Transformation. Ed. Miranda H. Ferrara and Michele P. LaMeau. Detroit: Gale, 2012. 267-270. Gale Virtual Reference Library. Web. June 10, 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Pandora began playing more advertisements per hour in certain geographies and demographics. Pandora normally plays no more than 6 advertisements per hour for free users.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilking|first1=Rick|title=Yes, you're hearing more ads on Pandora these days|url=http://qz.com/463470/yes-youre-hearing-more-ads-on-pandora-these-days/|website=Quartz|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Revenue ===\nPandora became fairly popular within just two years. Starting from 2010 to 2012 Pandora's registered users had increased from 45 million to 125 million. The company's revenue increased from $55 million to $274 million, in which a majority of it from advertising. In order to appeal to a large audience of consumers, Pandora offers ad-free access for $36 a year.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/16/business/media/pandora-courts-local-advertisers-by-reaching-a-narrow-audience.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first1=Ben | last1=Sisario | first2=Tanzina | last2=Vega | title=Pandora Courts Local Advertisers by Reaching a Narrow Audience | date=April 15, 2012}}</ref> During its 2011 fiscal year, Pandora reported $138 million in revenue with a $1.8 million net loss, excluding the cost of a special dividend associated with the IPO.<ref>Pandora Media, Inc. \"[http://services.corporate-ir.net/SEC.Enhanced/SecCapsule.aspx?c=227956&fid=7621947 Prospectus, SEC Form S-1].\" June 14, 2011. Retrieved June 22, 2011.</ref> Overall, Pandora has a 78% of Internet radio, and it has a 9.3% share of the U.S. [[public radio]]. Finally, in 2013 industry-wide total radio ad revenue increased to $17.6 billion in the U.S.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-05-20/pandora-can-extend-lead-in-online-music-cfo-herring-says.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Anthony | last=Palazzo | title=Pandora Can Extend Lead in Online Music, CFO Herring Says | date=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Pitch to advertisers ===\nPandora obtains its advertisers by explaining that the company reaches a narrower audience compared to terrestrial radio. \"Pandora's pitch to advertisers is that its technology can cater to consumers with far greater precision than radio \u2013 it can pinpoint listeners by age and sex, ZIP code or even musical taste.\"<ref name=\"nytimes.com\" />\n\n=== Methods of advertising ===\nThere are a few different methods of advertising on Pandora. Audio advertising comes in spots of 15 to 30 seconds, and run once every 20 minutes. However, users only encounter ads if they are engaging with the site, like contributing a thumbs up or a thumbs down when changing a song or station.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/16/business/media/pandora-courts-local-advertisers-by-reaching-a-narrow-audience.html|title=Pandora Courts Local Advertisers by Reaching a Narrow Audience|first1=Ben|last1=Sisario|first2=Tanzina|last2=Vega|date=April 15, 2012|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\nNext, there are [[banner ads]] which are featured on the wallpaper of the site. As noted by ''[[the New York Times]]'', banner ads are on Pandora in order \"to promote engagement, audio segments can be accompanied by clickable display ads offering coupons or product information.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" />\n\nAdvertising on Pandora works through a method of collecting [[data]] from the users online browsing activity. Once the [[data]] is collected, the company uses the data to show the user target ads. This process of advertising is also known as [[behavioral advertising]]. Pandora offers its users the option of submitting out of the targeted ads, by an opt-out configuration on its website. Opting-out will only prevent targeted ads, meaning users may continue to see generic (non-targeted ads) from these companies after they opt-out. Eventually, Pandora offers either targeted [[advertisements]] or generic advertisements for its non-subscribed users.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pandora.com/advertising/preferences|title=Your Advertising Choices|publisher=}}</ref> However, Pandora's advertising does not offer local content such as the local news, weather, traffic, and talk.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\" />\n\n=== Market segments ===\nPandora has created two [[market segment]]s, one for Spanish listeners, and another for English listeners. By creating multiple market segments, Pandora's advertising is customized to its users' needs. In order to create the first two market segments, the company cross-referenced its registered user data with [[U.S. census]]. Then, the cross reference allows the company to identify zip codes with high populations of Hispanic and Spanish-speaking people, and finally it ran tests overlaying the two data sets to infer which listeners fit into those buckets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adage.com/article/digital/pandora-past-tracking-cookie-mining-user-data/245269/ |title=Pandora Looks Past the Tracking Cookie By Mining User Data|author=Tim Peterson |date=November 14, 2013|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Internet radio stations]]\n* [[List of online music databases]]\n* [[List of streaming media systems]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/101/pandora.html Pandora featured in Fast Company]\n* [http://www.10zenmonkeys.com/2007/05/03/closing-pandoras-box-the-end-of-internet-radio/ Closing Pandora's Box: The End of Internet Radio?], May 3, 2007 interview with Tim Westergren\n* [http://news.cnet.com/8301-10784_3-9821318-7.html Pandora adds classical music]\n* [http://intruders.tv/en-tech/the-story-of-pandora-so-far-from-founder-tim-westergren/ Interview with Tim Westergren about the Music Genome Project and Pandora]\n* [http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/President-of-the-USA-Rocker-Challenges-Pandora-905442.htm Dave Dederer & nuTsie Challenge Pandora]\n* [http://www.inc.com/magazine/20071001/pandoras-long-strange-trip.html Inc. Magazine profile of Tim Westergren]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/08/technology/08pandora.html New York Times article on Tim Westergren and Pandora]\n* [https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2013/06/23/pink-floyd-royalties-pandora-column/2447445/ Pink Floyd: Pandora's Internet radio royalty ripoff] USA TODAY, 2013\n\n{{Music streaming services}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pandora Radio}}\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Online music and lyrics databases]]\n[[Category:Internet radio in the United States]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:BlackBerry software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:Music streaming services]]\n[[Category:Windows Phone software]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Oakland, California]]\n[[Category:2000 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 2000]]\n[[Category:Recommender systems]]\n[[Category:WatchOS software]]\n[[Category:2011 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:2019 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Sirius XM Satellite Radio]]\n[[Category:American corporate subsidiaries]]\n[[Category:American music websites]]\n", "name_user": "173.217.115.120", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pandora_Radio"}
