{"title_page": "Norton University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name            = <span style=\"color:#000066;\"><small>NORTON UNIVERSITY</small></span>\n|native_name     = '''\u179f\u17b6\u1780\u179b\u179c\u17b7\u1791\u17d2\u1799\u17b6\u179b\u17d0\u1799\u1793\u17d0\u179a\u178f\u17bb\u1793''' <br /><small>(Sakalvityealay Norton)</small>\n|image           = [[File:Norton Seal.jpg|180px|Norton University]]\n|image_name      = \n|image_size      = \n|caption         =\n|latin_name      = \n|motto           = Norton University Educating Tomorrow's Leaders\n\u179f\u17b6\u1780\u179b\u179c\u17b7\u1791\u17d2\u1799\u17b6\u179b\u17d0\u1799\u1793\u17d0\u179a\u178f\u17bb\u1793 \u17a2\u1797\u17b7\u179c\u178c\u17d2\u178d\u1793\u17cd \u17a2\u1793\u17b6\u1782\u178f \u17a2\u17d2\u1793\u1780\u178a\u17b9\u1780\u1793\u17b6\u17c6\n|tagline         =\n|established     = 1996 \n|type            = [[Private education|Private]]\n|endowment       = \n|staff           = \n|faculty         = \n|president       = \n|provost         = \n|principal       = \n|rector          = \n|chancellor      = Professor Chan Sok Khieng\n|vice_chancellor = Professor Un Van Thouen\n|dean            = \n|head_label      = \n|head            = \n|students        = \n|undergrad       = [[Bachelor's degree]]\n|postgrad        = [[Master's degree]]\n|doctoral        = \n|profess         =\n|city            = [[Phnom Penh]]\n|state           =\n|country         = {{flagicon|Cambodia}}[[Cambodia]]\n|campus          = [[Phnom Penh]], [[Cambodia]]\n|free_label      = \n|free            = \n|colors          =\n|colours         =\n|mascot          = The Lion\n|fightsong       =\n|nickname        = NU\n|affiliations    = \n|footnotes       =\n|website         = [http://www.norton-u.com/ www.norton-u.com]\n|address         = St. Keo Chenda, Sangkat Chroy Changvar, Khan Chroy Changvar, Phnom Penh, Cambodia.\n|coor            = {{coord|11.5880|104.9301|type:edu_region:KH|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|logo            = [[File:norton-u.png|upright=1.0|Norton University]]\n}}{{Contains Khmer text}}\n'''Norton University''' ({{lang-km|\u179f\u17b6\u1780\u179b\u179c\u17b7\u1791\u17d2\u1799\u17b6\u179b\u17d0\u1799 \u1793\u17d0\u179a\u178f\u17bb\u1793}}, NU) is a private university in [[Cambodia]] registered with the Ministry of Education, Youth and Sport.<ref>Ministry of Education, Youth and Sport website, Private Higher Education Institutions [http://www.moeys.gov.kh/en/about_moeys/private_hedu.htm] Retrieved, November 12, 2008</ref> It was established in 1996. The University was one of the first private Cambodian educational institutions.\n\nIn 2006, Tom Chandler, a 3-D modeling specialist from [[Monash University]] in [[Melbourne]] was invited to Norton as a senior visiting fellow. The aim of the fellowship was to introduce architecture and science students to specialised animation and modeling techniques and allow them to learn to digitally render their own heritage using 3-D techniques.<ref>''Ruins to 3-D riches: recreating the Khmers'', [[The Age]], February 26, 2007 [http://www.theage.com.au/news/education-news/ruins-to-3d-riches-recreating-the-khmers/2007/02/24/1171734032313.html?page=fullpage]</ref>\n\nNorton university is considered to be the '''Best IT Education Center in Cambodia''' years after its establishment, and was chosen by [[National ICT Development Authority]] (NiDA), [[Ministry of Post-Telecommunications]] (MPTC), [[International Data Group]] (IDG) to receive the award, and that official honor in 2010.<ref>[http://www.norton-u.com/misc/?LinkID=168111&lsn=&len=&lpg=&eid=72 Norton University the Best IT Education Center in Cambodia]</ref> The university has two campus both based in [[Phnom Penh]]. The current Rector, and Vice Rector of Norton University are '''Professor [[Chan Sok Khieng]]''' and '''Professor [[Ung Vann Thoeun|Un Van Thouen]]''', respectively.\n\n==Courses==\n\n===Under Graduates (Bachelor's Degree)===\n\n====College of Arts, Humanities and Languages====\n\n'''Degree'''\n\n# Bachelor of Arts, in Teaching English as a Foreign Language\n# Bachelor of Arts in English Communication\n# Bachelor of Arts in English Interpretation and Translation\n\n====College of Sciences====\n\n=====<u>Computer Studies</u>=====\n\n'''Degree''' : ''Bachelor of Science in Computing Information (BSc)''.\n\n'''Course Summary'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| 1st Year || \n* Office Application I\n* Accounting I\n* English language I\n* Introduction to business\n* College Algebra\n* Theory of electricity\n* Accounting II\n* Programming Methodology in C\n* Digital Design\n* English Language II\n* Discrete Mathematics\n* Office Application II\n|-\n| 2nd Year ||\n* Data Structure and Algorithms in C/C++\n* Programming in C/C++\n* English Language III\n* Microprocessors\n* Database System\n* Statistic Theories\n* Database Management System\n* Design and Analysis of Algorithms:\n* Computer Graphics in C/C++\n* English Language IV\n* Data Communication\n|-\n| 3rd Year || \n* Visual Basic Programming\n* Statistical Analysis\n* Advanced Database Management System\n* Advanced Visual Basic Programming\n* Web Site Development and programming\n* System Analysis and design\n* Computer Network I Networking theory\n* Object-Oriented Methodology and programming in C++\n* Computer Architectures\n* Java Programming\n* Software Project Management\n|-\n| 4th Year ||\n* Computer Networks II MS NOS Administration\n* Linux Operating System\n* Advance web Site Development and Programming\n* Operating System Theories\n* Advanced Java programming\n* Method of Researches\n* Thesis writing\n* E-commerce Technologies\n* GIS System\n* Advance Linux operating System\n* Management Information System\n* Thesis Writing\n|}\n\n=====<u>Civil Engineering</u>=====\n\n'''Degree''' : ''Bachelor Engineering (BEng)''\n'''Structure and Components'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| General Basic Courses || \n* Humanities Courses\n* Social Science\n* English Language\n* Sciences and Mathematics\n|-\n| Engineering Courses || \n* Engineering Drawing\n* Materials and Building Construction\n* Major in Engineering Survey\n* Major in Concrete Technology\n* Major in Theory of Structures and Structure Design\n* Hydraulics and Hydrology\n* Major in Water Supply and Wastewater Treatment\n* Major in Geo-technique and Foundation Engineering\n* Electrical for Building\n* Major in Road and Bridge Construction\n* Major in Contract Procedures and Estimation\n* Major in Computer Application and Construction Management\n* Major in Ecology\n|-\n|}\n\n=====<u>Electronics & Electricities</u>=====\n\n=====<u>Architecture</u>=====\n\n===Post Graduates (Master's Degree)===\n\n==Partner Institution==\n===Malaysia===\n*[[Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman]]<ref name=\"UTARUniversityPartners\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.utar.edu.my/dcinternet/index.jsp?fcatid=7819|title=University Partners - Division of Community and International Networking|publisher=Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman(UTAR)|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.norton-u.com/ The Norton University website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Education in Phnom Penh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox University\n|name            = <span style=\"color:#000066;\"><small>NORTON UNIVERSITY</small></span>\n|native_name     = '''\u179f\u17b6\u1780\u179b\u179c\u17b7\u1791\u17d2\u1799\u17b6\u179b\u17d0\u1799\u1793\u17d0\u179a\u178f\u17bb\u1793''' <br /><small>(Sakalvityealay Norton)</small>\n|image           = [[File:Norton Seal.jpg|180px|Norton University]]\n|image_name      = \n|image_size      = \n|caption         =\n|latin_name      = \n|motto           = Norton University Educating Tomorrow's Leaders\n\u179f\u17b6\u1780\u179b\u179c\u17b7\u1791\u17d2\u1799\u17b6\u179b\u17d0\u1799\u1793\u17d0\u179a\u178f\u17bb\u1793 \u17a2\u1797\u17b7\u179c\u178c\u17d2\u178d\u1793\u17cd \u17a2\u1793\u17b6\u1782\u178f \u17a2\u17d2\u1793\u1780\u178a\u17b9\u1780\u1793\u17b6\u17c6\n|tagline         =\n|established     = 1996 \n|type            = [[Private education|Private]]\n|endowment       = \n|staff           = \n|faculty         = \n|president       = \n|provost         = \n|principal       = \n|rector          = \n|chancellor      = Professor Chan Sok Khieng\n|vice_chancellor = Professor Un Van Thouen\n|dean            = \n|head_label      = \n|head            = \n|students        = \n|undergrad       = [[Bachelor's degree]]\n|postgrad        = [[Master's degree]]\n|doctoral        = \n|profess         =\n|city            = [[Phnom Penh]]\n|state           =\n|country         = {{flagicon|Cambodia}}[[Cambodia]]\n|campus          = [[Phnom Penh]], [[Cambodia]]\n|free_label      = \n|free            = \n|colors          =\n|colours         =\n|mascot          = The Lion\n|fightsong       =\n|nickname        = NU\n|affiliations    = \n|footnotes       =\n|website         = [http://www.norton-u.com/ www.norton-u.com]\n|address         = St. Keo Chenda, Sangkat Chroy Changvar, Khan Chroy Changvar, Phnom Penh, Cambodia.\n|coor            = {{coord|11.5880|104.9301|type:edu_region:KH|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|logo            = [[File:norton-u.png|upright=1.0|Norton University]]\n}}{{Contains Khmer text}}\n'''Norton University''' ({{lang-km|\u179f\u17b6\u1780\u179b\u179c\u17b7\u1791\u17d2\u1799\u17b6\u179b\u17d0\u1799 \u1793\u17d0\u179a\u178f\u17bb\u1793}}, NU) is a private university in [[Cambodia]] registered with the Ministry of Education, Youth and Sport.<ref>Ministry of Education, Youth and Sport website, Private Higher Education Institutions [http://www.moeys.gov.kh/en/about_moeys/private_hedu.htm] Retrieved, November 12, 2008</ref> It was established in 1996. The University was one of the first private Cambodian educational institutions.\n\nIn 2006, Tom Chandler, a 3-D modeling specialist from [[Monash University]] in [[Melbourne]] was invited to Norton as a senior visiting fellow. The aim of the fellowship was to introduce architecture and science students to specialised animation and modeling techniques and allow them to learn to digitally render their own heritage using 3-D techniques.<ref>''Ruins to 3-D riches: recreating the Khmers'', [[The Age]], February 26, 2007 [http://www.theage.com.au/news/education-news/ruins-to-3d-riches-recreating-the-khmers/2007/02/24/1171734032313.html?page=fullpage]</ref>\n\nNorton university is considered to be the '''Best IT Education Center in Cambodia''' years after its establishment, and was chosen by [[National ICT Development Authority]] (NiDA), [[Ministry of Post-Telecommunications]] (MPTC), [[International Data Group]] (IDG) to receive the award, and that official honor in 2010.<ref>[http://www.norton-u.com/misc/?LinkID=168111&lsn=&len=&lpg=&eid=72 Norton University the Best IT Education Center in Cambodia]</ref> The university has two campus both based in [[Phnom Penh]]. The current Rector, and Vice Rector of Norton University are '''Professor [[Chan Sok Khieng]]''' and '''Professor [[Ung Vann Thoeun|Un Van Thouen]]''', respectively.\n\n==Courses==\n\n===Under Graduates (Bachelor's Degree)===\n\n====College of Arts, Humanities and Languages====\n\n'''Degree'''\n\n# Bachelor of Arts, in Teaching English as a Foreign Language\n# Bachelor of Arts in English Communication\n# Bachelor of Arts in English Interpretation and Translation\n\n====College of Sciences====\n\n=====<u>Computer Studies</u>=====\n\n'''Degree''' : ''Bachelor of Science in Computing Information (BSc)''.\n\n'''Course Summary'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| 1st Year || \n* Office Application I\n* Accounting I\n* English language I\n* Introduction to business\n* College Algebra\n* Theory of electricity\n* Accounting II\n* Programming Methodology in C\n* Digital Design\n* English Language II\n* Discrete Mathematics\n* Office Application II\n|-\n| 2nd Year ||\n* Data Structure and Algorithms in C/C++\n* Programming in C/C++\n* English Language III\n* Microprocessors\n* Database System\n* Statistic Theories\n* Database Management System\n* Design and Analysis of Algorithms:\n* Computer Graphics in C/C++\n* English Language IV\n* Data Communication\n|-\n| 3rd Year || \n* Visual Basic Programming\n* Statistical Analysis\n* Advanced Database Management System\n* Advanced Visual Basic Programming\n* Web Site Development and programming\n* System Analysis and design\n* Computer Network I Networking theory\n* Object-Oriented Methodology and programming in C++\n* Computer Architectures\n* Java Programming\n* Software Project Management\n|-\n| 4th Year ||\n* Computer Networks II MS NOS Administration\n* Linux Operating System\n* Advance web Site Development and Programming\n* Operating System Theories\n* Advanced Java programming\n* Method of Researches\n* Thesis writing\n* E-commerce Technologies\n* GIS System\n* Advance Linux operating System\n* Management Information System\n* Thesis Writing\n|}\n\n=====<u>Civil Engineering</u>=====\n\n'''Degree''' : ''Bachelor Engineering (BEng)''\n'''Structure and Components'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| General Basic Courses || \n* Humanities Courses\n* Social Science\n* English Language\n* Sciences and Mathematics\n|-\n| Engineering Courses || \n* Engineering Drawing\n* Materials and Building Construction\n* Major in Engineering Survey\n* Major in Concrete Technology\n* Major in Theory of Structures and Structure Design\n* Hydraulics and Hydrology\n* Major in Water Supply and Wastewater Treatment\n* Major in Geo-technique and Foundation Engineering\n* Electrical for Building\n* Major in Road and Bridge Construction\n* Major in Contract Procedures and Estimation\n* Major in Computer Application and Construction Management\n* Major in Ecology\n|-\n|}\n\n=====<u>Electronics & Electricities</u>=====\n\n=====<u>Architecture</u>=====\n\n===Post Graduates (Master's Degree)===\n\n==Partner Institution==\n===Malaysia===\n*[[Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman]]<ref name=\"UTARUniversityPartners\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.utar.edu.my/dcinternet/index.jsp?fcatid=7819|title=University Partners - Division of Community and International Networking|publisher=Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman(UTAR)|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.norton-u.com/ The Norton University website]\n\n[[Category:Universities in Cambodia]]\n[[Category:Education in Phnom Penh]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norton_University"}
{"title_page": "Northwestern University in Qatar", "text_new": "{{advert|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name        = Northwestern University in Qatar\n| established = 2008\n| type        = Private\n| president   = [[Morton Schapiro]]\n| dean        = [[Everette E. Dennis]]\n| campus      = [[Education City]]\n| mascot      = Willie the Wildcat\n| website     = {{URL |www.qatar.northwestern.edu}}\n| image       = northwestern-university-qatar.png\n| location    = [[Doha, Qatar]]\n| colors      = Purple (official) and white (unofficial)\n}}\n\n'''Northwestern University in Qatar''' (NU-Q) is [[Northwestern University]]\u2019s campus in [[Education City]], [[Doha, Qatar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2008/08/qatar.html|title=Inaugural Classes Begin at Northwestern in Qatar|work=Northwestern University|author=Pat Vaughan Tremmel|date=18 August 2008|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> founded in partnership with [[Qatar Foundation]] in 2008.\n\nNorthwestern University's Qatar campus offers a liberal arts and media education with undergraduate degrees awarded in [[communication]], journalism and strategic communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/provost/policies/handbook/handbook.pdf|title=Northwestern University Handbook|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"studyabroad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.studyabroaduniversities.com/UniversityReview.aspx?University=Northwestern-University-in-Qatar&UniversityId=12874|title=Northwestern University in Qatar|work=studyabroaduniversities.com}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:New NU-Q building.tif|left|thumb|240x240px|Northwestern University in Qatar]]\nHaving been approached in 2006 by the [[Qatar Foundation|Qatar Foundation for Education, Science and Community Development]], Northwestern agreed the following year to open its campus at [[Education City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://civiceducationproject.org/qatar-foundation-and-northwestern-university-agree-on-branch-campus-at-education-city/index.html|title=Civic Education Project|work=civiceducationproject.org}}</ref> The inaugural NU-Q Class of 2012 began studies in August 2008.<ref name=\"thepeninsulaqatar.com\" /> Additional classes have been added each year, and the university has established strong ties with local organizations, partnering with media groups and collaborating with a number of regional initiatives to generate additional educational and professional opportunities for its students.\n\nA number of notable journalists, scholars, and media professionals have addressed students and faculty at Northwestern University in Qatar, including [[Fareed Zakaria]] of CNN's ''Fareed Zakaria GPS''; journalist [[Evan Osnos]] of [[The New Yorker]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulf-times.com/|title=Gulf times- Qatar\u2019s top-selling English daily newspaper - Homepage|website=Gulf-Times|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> television journalist [[Tim Sebastian]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/error|title=Error Page|website=Gulf-Times|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Iranian-American journalist [[Roxana Saberi]]; Carlos Van Meek, former head of output for Al Jazeera English; Arthur Sulzberger, publisher of the ''New York Times''; Jeff Cole, head of the World Internet Project; [[Rami George Khouri|Rami Khouri]], editor of the ''Beirut Daily Star'', and [[Sophia Al Maria]], author and filmmaker.\n\nThe university graduated its first class in spring 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ida.gov.sg/doc/About%20us/About_Us_Level2/20071005103551/02_Digital_Media_and_Entertainment.pdf|title=IDA|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Academic Programs==\nThe curriculum leading to the award of the Bachelor of Science in Communication degree is based on that of the [[Northwestern University School of Communication]] at Northwestern's Evanston campus. Communication students at NU-Q pursue a major in Media Industries and Technologies, which combines elements of the Communication Studies and Radio/TV/Film majors offered at the Northwestern University home campus in the United States.<ref name=\"thepeninsulaqatar.com\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.thepeninsulaqatar.com/component/content/article/349-qatar-newsarchive/83702.html|title=The Peninsula|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Class at Northwestern University in Qatar.jpg|left|thumb|240x240px|Class at Northwestern University in Qatar]]\nThe curriculum leading to the award of the Bachelor of Science in Journalism degree draws on that of the [[Medill School of Journalism|Medill School of Journalism, Media, Integrated Marketing Communications]] at Northwestern's Evanston campus. This program is accredited by the Accrediting Council on Education in Journalism and Mass Communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2009/02/qatar.html|title=Taking Northwestern Overseas: Campus Life in Qatar: Northwestern University News|work=northwestern.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ku.edu/~acejmc/STUDENT/PROGLIST.SHTML|title=ACEJMC-accredited programs|work=ku.edu|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726094439/http://www2.ku.edu/~acejmc/STUDENT/PROGLIST.SHTML|archivedate=2014-07-26}}</ref> Liberal arts courses are provided by Northwestern's [[Weinberg College of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zawya.com/story.cfm/sidZAWYA20100106072004/Three%20Endowed%20Professorships%20To%20Be%20Named%20After%20Emir%20Of%20Qatar|title=Zawya|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nNU-Q courses are modeled closely on those offered at Northwestern University campus in the United States, although adjustments have been made because the Qatar campus courses are taught in a 15-week semester system, rather than a 10-week quarter system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ameinfo.com/206867.html|title=Business Real Estate News - Technology - Travel Guide|website=www.ameinfo.com|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"northwestern\">{{cite web|url=http://qatar-news.northwestern.edu/2011/06/junior-from-qatar-campus-reflects-on-two-quarters-in-evanston/|title=Northwestern University in Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Additionally, courses with particular relevance to the region are offered at NU-Q.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.explore-qatar.com/qatar-today/new-face-journalism|title=Explore Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> In 2012, NU-Q secured permission from the Board of Trustees to make its own academic appointments.<ref name=\"northwestern.edu\">[http://qatar-news.northwestern.edu/year-in-review-2012-13/]</ref>\nNU-Q's academic programs provide various opportunities for students to participate in international programs. Students in the Journalism and Strategic Communication Program are required to complete a junior year residency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/academics/journalism-program/journalism-residency.html|title=Northwestern University in Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Juniors in the Communication Program are eligible to apply for the Evanston exchange.<ref name=\"northwestern\" /> Shorter international academic trips are offered at various times throughout the year. Past destinations have included [[Turkey]], [[Switzerland]], [[Italy]], [[South Africa]], [[France]], [[India]] and the [[United States|USA]]. All students are eligible their sophomore year to apply for a one-week trip to the [[Northwestern University]] Evanston campus, which takes place in May of each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/academics/journalism-program/reporting-trips.html|title=Northwestern university in Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Northwestern University in Qatar foyer.jpg|thumb|240x240px|Northwestern University in Qatar campus]]\nNU-Q students can access courses at the five other American universities located in [[Education City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qf.org.qa/news-center/news/news-details?item=130|title=Qatar Foundation|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nNorthwestern's Qatar Campus is one of the best journalism and communication schools in the world. Degrees awarded by Northwestern University's Qatar campus are accredited by the Higher Learning Commission of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]].\n\n=== Pre-College Programs ===\nNU-Q offers an annual [http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/education/pre-college-programs/summer-media-institute/ summer media program to high school students] combining aspects of the Journalism and Strategic Communication and Communication Programs. NU-Q also offers workshops to high school students periodically throughout the school year.\n\n== Funding ==\nSimilar to other universities with campuses in Education City, Northwestern's facilities are entirely paid for by Qatar. In 2014, Northwestern received $45.3 million to run the Doha campus.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/in-qatars-education-city-us-colleges-are-building-an-academic-oasis/2015/12/06/6b538702-8e01-11e5-ae1f-af46b7df8483_story.html|title=In Qatar\u2019s Education City, U.S. colleges are building an academic oasis|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> Also like other Doha campuses of U.S. universities, Qatari students at Northwestern have their tuition covered by Qatar. Students of other nationalities either pay for their own tuition or can sometimes receive scholarship money. {{As of|2016}}, tuition for the school is about $52,000 per year.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/admissions/financial-aid/tuition.html|title=Northwestern University in Qatar Tuition and Fees|last=|first=|date=|website=Northwestern University in Qatar|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:Northwestern University in Qatar newsroom.jpg|left|thumb|240x240px|The University's fully automated newsroom features some of the most advanced technology in broadcast and production.]]\n\n== Facilities ==\n\nNU-Q's permanent home in Education City was designed by American architect [[Antoine Predock]]. Predock traveled around the world, deriving inspiration from desert structures to give NU-Q's new building a look and feel appropriate to Qatar's culture, climate, and location.\n\nNorthwestern moved into its permanent facility in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/life/new-home.html|title=Northwestern University in Qatar - New Home|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The four-story building is more than 500,000 square feet and has achieved a [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Gold Certification.\n\nThe university also will soon open The Media Majlis at Northwestern University in Qatar, the first museum in the Arab world dedicated to exploring the content of media, journalism and communication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/mediamajlis/index.html|title=The Media Majlis at Northwestern University in Qatar - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>\n\nLocated on the NU-Q campus, the bilingual (Arabic and English) museum will feature interactive exhibitions, discussion programs and other projects examining media, journalism and communication through global, regional and local/Qatar lenses.&nbsp; An inaugural exhibit will examine a century's worth of film history as shaped by notions of Arab identity. The Media Majlis, Qatar's first university museum, will offer free admission to students, faculty and the public.\n\n== Research ==\nIn 2013, NU-Q launched the school's signature research project, an annual survey of media use in the MENA region. ''Media Use in the Middle East'' in 2013,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://menamediasurvey.northwestern.edu/|title=Media Use in the Middle East 2013 {{!}} Northwestern University in Qatar|website=menamediasurvey.northwestern.edu|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/survey/2014/|title=Entertainment Media Use in the Middle East|website=www.mideastmedia.org|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/survey/2015/|title=Media Use in the Middle East, 2015 \u00b7 Media Use In The Middle East|website=www.mideastmedia.org|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/survey/2016/|title=MEDIA USE IN THE MIDDLE EAST, 2016 \u00b7 Media Use in the Middle East|website=www.mideastmedia.org|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>  and 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/survey/2017/|title=MEDIA USE IN THE MIDDLE EAST, 2017 \u00b7 Media Use in the Middle East, 2017|website=www.mideastmedia.org|access-date=2017-11-14}}</ref> as well the report, ''Media Industries in the Middle East'', 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/industry/2016/|title=MENA Media Industry \u00b7 MENA Media Industry|website=www.mideastmedia.org|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> revealed regional attitudes about government censorship, press freedom, the morality of content, entertainment preferences and overall consumption habits, as well as provided an overview of the most prevalent business models across the MENA media landscape. NU-Q's research has been cited by academic institutions and think tanks (e.g., USC Annenberg School Center for the Digital Future,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/2015-World-Internet-Report.pdf|title=2015 World Internet Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Brookings Institution<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/techtank/2015/05/14/the-search-for-media-reality-in-the-arab-middle-east/|title=The search for media reality in the Arab Middle East {{!}} Brookings Institution|date=2017-02-15|newspaper=Brookings|access-date=2017-02-15|language=en-US}}</ref>) as well as news media outlets (e.g.,''Christian Science Monitor'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Global-News/2013/0617/New-poll-shows-growing-Arab-trust-in-regional-press|title=New poll shows growing Arab trust in regional press|last=Zirulnick|first=Ariel|date=2013-06-17|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2017-02-15|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> ''CNN'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/04/23/world/meast/middle-east-hollywood-films-censorship-survey/index.html|title=Hollywood movies in Arab countries: A love and hate relationship|author=Yenni Kwok, for|website=CNN|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> ''The Atlantic'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/04/how-people-in-the-middle-east-actually-use-social-media/275246/|title=How People in the Middle East Actually Use Social Media|last=Wood|first=Everette E. Dennis, Justin D. Martin, and Robb|newspaper=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-02-15|language=en-US}}</ref> ''Al Jazeera'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/02/shrinking-space-media-arab-world-150209093710948.html|title=The shrinking space for media in the Arab world|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> ''Al-Arabiya''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/media/television-and-radio/2016/04/21/Festival-of-Media-Seven-digital-only-radio-stations-coming-to-Dubai-.html|title=Festival of Media: Seven digital-only radio stations coming to Dubai|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>) around the world.\n\n==Students and Student Life==\nApproximately half the student body is Qatari; however, regardless of passport, many students come from Qatar, representing 32 nationalities across the student body. There are about 300 students enrolled in the school.\n\nNU-Q has worked to integrate some western values into its Qatar campus. For example, there are many female students that attend NU-Q. There have been some concerns that this integration, which is not as common in Qatar can be slightly difficult to implement. Qatar adheres to [[Salafi movement|Salafism]], which is one of the most fundamental sects of Islam and dictates all aspects of society and life in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2014/02/11/northwestern-university-s-qatar-campus|title=Northwestern University\u2019s Qatar Campus|website=Chicago Tonight {{!}} WTTW|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/libya/2012-09-19/sources-salafi-conduct|title=The Sources of Salafi Conduct|date=2012-09-20|website=Foreign Affairs|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nNU-Q students have access to the full range of student activities offered to all Education City students, including the Hamad bin Khalifa University Student Center, Recreation Center, clubs, organizations and athletic leagues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/life-nu-q/index.html|title=Campus Life|work=northwestern.edu}}</ref>\n\nNU-Q is the host of many film and production related events, such as THIMUN Qatar Northwestern Film Festival and the NU-Q Student Media and Research Award].\n\nStudents also participate in a wide variety of leadership, service and experiential learning initiatives both in [[Doha]] and internationally.\n\nIn addition, students have access to and participate in a range of athletics, activities, and clubs.\n\n=== Students in the Field ===\n[[File:NU-Q walkway.jpg|left|thumb|280x280px|Northwestern University in Qatar campus]]\nStudent have tackled subjects that are considered controversial in Qatar and throughout the Middle East. One NU-Q graduate was nominated for a student academy award for his film,''100 Steps'', which tells the story of a young boy in Pakistan who finds that his local religious school has served as a front for a radical extremists\u2019 recruitment camp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2016/08-zali-student-academy-award-nom.html|title=NU-Q graduate nominated for student Oscar - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> ''Convict of 302'', a documentary by two NU-Q students about Pakistan's death penalty and anti-terrorism laws, screened at a consortium sponsored by the Pulitzer Center on Crisis Reporting in Washington, DC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2016/12-Pulitzer-fellows.html|title=NU-Q students screen documentary in Washington, DC - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>\n\nStudents have also written stories about working conditions at local development sites in Qatar, domestic abuse<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/in-qatars-education-city-us-colleges-are-building-an-academic-oasis/2015/12/06/6b538702-8e01-11e5-ae1f-af46b7df8483_story.html|title=In Qatar\u2019s Education City, U.S. colleges are building an academic oasis|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> and women's issues.\n\nAnother NU-Q graduate, Ismaeel Naar, was named Outstanding Young Arab Journalist of the year in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2016/12-Ismaeel-Naar.html|title=NU-Q alum named Outstanding Young Arab Journalist - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>\n\n'''Residency'''\n\nJournalism juniors spend ten weeks working in a professional organization somewhere around the world. Assignments have included the ''Financial Times'', ''National Geographic'', ''Huffington Post'', Grayling Public Relations, Qatar Foundation International and ''Vogue''.The goal of the Journalism Residency is for students to get the kinds of hands-on experience that helps them develop new skills, test old skills, work under deadline pressure, hone their news judgment, sharpen their fact-checking and research skills, build confidence in their capabilities and explore new career paths not previously considered. This is a required component of the B.S. in journalism degree program.\n\n'''Academic Trips'''\n\nThis program is open to NU-Q students and assists them with learning about how organizations work in other countries. Previous trips have included Turkey, Switzerland, Italy, United Kingdom and the United States.\n\n'''Service Learning and Leadership'''\n\nNU-Q students can participate in annual Spring Break Service Learning Trips to global destinations. The goal of the trips are to connect students to the needs of the larger worldwide community, provide insight and understanding of the historical and socio-political context of the visited country, and build a strong sense of global citizenship and commitment. Students complete assigned projects and reflections as part of the experience. Trip destinations have included Brazil, China, India, Morocco, South Africa, Tunisia, Zambia, and more.\n\n'''Evanston Exchange'''\n\nStudents who are a pursuing the BS degree in communication can participate in the Evanston Communication Exchange Program during spring semester of their junior year, where they study at Northwestern's home campus, located near Chicago in Evanston, Illinois, USA.\n\n==Leadership==\nThe leadership of NU-Q is appointed by the Northwestern University Provost, in consultation with the Qatar Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynorthwestern.com/campus/international-search-for-nu-q-dean-john-margolis-replacement-begins-1.2265477|title=Daily Northwestern|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Craig LaMay is the acting dean. An educator, author and media expert, NU-Q's dean Dr. Everette E. Dennis was appointed in June 2011. The founding dean was Dr. John Margolis, an associate provost at Northwestern University who served from 2008 to 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynorthwestern.com/campus/founding-dean-of-northwestern-in-qatar-retires-1.2428764|title=Daily Northwestern|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynorthwestern.com/campus/new-nu-q-dean-hopes-to-mature-institution-1.2603108|title=Daily Northwestern|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Gregory Ferrell Lowe is director of the Communication Program. Mary Dedinsky is director of the Journalism and Strategic Communication Program. Hariclea Zengos is senior associate dean for research. Kathleen Hewett-Smith is director of the Liberal Arts program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/about/leadership.html|title=Leadership - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|access-date=2016-10-30}}</ref>\n\nThe NU-Q staff provide the range of support services expected in an American college or university, including professionally staffed offices for admissions, academic and personal counseling, student activities, student records, information technology, human resources, finance, marketing/public relations, and facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/about/our-people/staff/index.html|title=Northwestern University in Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> The collections of the professionally staffed NU-Q library focus on media issues, and students and faculty also have access to all electronic resources available at the Northwestern University Evanston campus and to the services of inter-library loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.northwestern.edu/libraries-collections/qatar-campus/library-services|title=Qatar Library Services|work=northwestern.edu}}</ref> A production facilities department provides support for the media-intensive work of students and faculty at NU-Q.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailyq.org/blog/2011/02/09/nu-q-connects-with-qatar-high-school-students/|title=NU-Q connects with Qatar high school students|work=thedailyq.org}}</ref>\n\n==Faculty==\nThere are 38 faculty members at NU-Q.\n\nMany of the faculty and instructors at NU-Q are not tenured which puts some limits on academic freedom for the professors. This leaves these professors answerable to the NU-Q Dean, a situation that is not dissimilar to faculty members at Northwestern's Evanston Campus. In Qatar, however, a report by Stephen Eiesenman, former President of Northwestern Faculty Senate, pointed out that the Dean has much more authority than in the United States. Additionally, if a faculty member is no longer employed by NU-Q, they must leave the country, forcing them to uproot their lives there, a situation which no doubt puts pressure on the faculty member to work within the confines of a more limited set of academic and intellectual freedoms. Additionally, faculty members at NU-Q are not eligible for tenure unless they are visiting from the Evanston or Chicago campuses.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMany professors at Doha campuses of U.S. universities are incentivized to trade in their teaching positions in the U.S. for ones in Qatar with a salary premium, housing arrangements and research funding.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Community ==\nIn addition to its core mission of providing undergraduate education to its students, NU-Q seeks to serve as a regional center for issues related to communication and journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2010/12/nuq-dean-everette-dennis.html|title=Everette E. Dennis Named Dean of Northwestern University in Qatar: Northwestern University News|work=northwestern.edu}}</ref> Often in collaboration with local, regional, or international organizations, NU-Q sponsors seminars and colloquia on topics related to the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ameinfo.com/189743.html|title=Business Real Estate News - Technology - Travel Guide|website=www.ameinfo.com|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> NU-Q also sponsors short, non-credit programs for pre-college students, which are designed to expose them to developments in media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/qatar/465-nu-q-reaches-out-to-local-high-schools.html|title=The Peninsula Qatar - NU-Q reaches out to local high schools|work=thepeninsulaqatar.com}}</ref>\n\nOutside of the NU-Q and Education City communities, freedom of speech is highly limited and anyone who threatened \u201csocial values\u201d or Qatar's \u201cgeneral order\u201d through any forms of news, photos, videos or audio recordings can be sentenced to prison. A report by the former President of the Northwestern University Faculty Senate conducted during his tenure as President highlighted that these implicit community values seem to be ingrained in the students, who seemed to willingly comply with these restrictions both intentionally and unintentionally.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Partnerships ==\nNU-Q has undertaken several initiatives in media education and community outreach. In 2013, NU-Q began the biannual Qatar Media Industries Forum (QMIF), bringing together top representatives in publishing, electronic media, digital media, public relations and advertising to discuss and assess the present and future of Qatar's media landscape.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/events/media-industries-forum/|title=Qatar Media Industries Forum - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> In 2012, the school also established separate partnerships with the [[Doha Film Institute]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.qatarisbooming.com/article/nu-q-partners-doha-film-institute-support-local-media-year%E2%80%99s-dtff|title=NU-Q partners with Doha Film Institute to support local media at this year\u2019s DTFF|last=editor_CM|date=2012-11-03|newspaper=Qatar is Booming|access-date=2017-02-15|language=en}}</ref> and [[Al Jazeera Media Network|Al Jazeera Network]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/docs/publications/annual-report/2012-13-Annual-Report.pdf|title=Unifying Northwestern University in Qatar: Year in Review 2012-2013|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> NU-Q also partners with the [[Qatar Computing Research Institute|Qatar Computer Research Institute]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2016/02-mou-qcri.html|title=NU-Q signs landmark MOU with QCRI for media industry research and knowledge sharing - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\nNorthwestern, as with all other U.S. universities with campuses in Doha has been the subject of ongoing criticism of whether a campus in Doha is an appropriate endeavor. In an interview with ''Gulf News Journal'', Herbert London, president of the London Center for Policy Research and a senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute, said \u201cuniversities I think have compromised themselves\u201d by having campuses in a country like Qatar where academic freedom and freedom of the press are severely limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gulfnewsjournal.com/stories/510548507-roots-of-american-universities-grow-deeper-in-qatar-drawing-criticism|title=Roots of American universities grow deeper in Qatar, drawing criticism|last=|first=|date=2015-06-08|website=Gulf News Journal|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nAlong with other universities with campuses in Qatar, Northwestern has received criticism for accepting money from Qatar due to their alleged support of [[terrorism]] worldwide and their abysmal human rights record, especially in the lead up to the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]]. Some question if universities who profit from campuses in Qatar are thereby complicit in Qatar's alleged sponsorship of terrorism and human rights abuses.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gulfnewsjournal.com/stories/510712102-advocate-questions-motive-behind-qatar-s-financial-ties-to-u-s-colleges|title=Advocate questions motive behind Qatar's financial ties to U.S. colleges|last=|first=|date=2016-04-08|website=Gulf News Journal|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gulfnewsjournal.com/stories/510639673-while-u-s-universities-see-dollar-signs-in-qatari-partnerships-some-cry-foul|title=While U.S. universities see dollar signs in Qatari partnerships, some cry foul|last=|first=|date=2015-09-24|website=Gulf News Journal|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\n===Freedom of Speech===\nConcerns have been raised over whether journalism can be taught effectively in a country with limited freedom of expression and where reports of censorship arise from time to time.  Additionally, some members of Northwestern's faculty have expressed \u201cdissatisfaction with the academic and free speech protections\u201d. In an interview with the Washington Post, former Northwestern Faculty Senate President, Stephen Eisenman, said that \u201cteaching journalism as an enterprise in which you must first learn what not to ask, is no kind of journalism instruction at all\u201d and continued that at NU-Q this was \u201clikely a matter of encouraging some enquiries and making others strange, awkward, rude or unserious\u201d.<ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2015/12/17/northwestern-professor-raises-questions-about-its-branch-in-qatar/|title=Northwestern professor raises questions about its branch in Qatar|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref><ref name=\":3\"/><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2016/02/23/northwestern-university-will-stay-another-decade-in-qatar/|title=Northwestern University will stay a decade longer in Qatar|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn an article by The Washington Post, Susan Dun, an assistant professor of communication at NU-Q said that some professors do exercise caution with statements, written work, or speeches that may reach a wider audience than just the Education City community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2015/12/17/can-u-s-universities-thrive-in-the-persian-gulf-these-scholars-say-yes/|title=Can U.S. universities thrive in the Persian Gulf? These scholars say yes.|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nMohanalakashmi Rajakumar, who taught English at Northwestern, VCU and Georgetown in Qatar published a book called \u201cLove Comes Later\u201d that was banned by Qatar in 2015 with no explanation due to the country's strict censorship policies.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nStudents at Northwestern have said that they face challenges due to the lack of first amendment rights protecting the media. Students have been harassed and intimidated when trying to capture images that would be considered routine or not offensive in the U.S. Some faculty members maintain that this teaches students persistence and creativity in overcoming obstacles to report on a story.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEverette Dennis, the dean of NU-Q led a six-nation survey in 2015 that was financed by the Qatar National Research Fund and asked questions such as if people think their country is \u201cheaded in the right direction\u201d. While the UAE, Egypt, Tunisia, Lebanon and Saudi Arabia all had answers to the question, there was no data from Qatar as the government blocked the question from being asked to survey participants.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/ Northwestern University in Qatar] official website\n\n{{Northwestern}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Education City]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name        = Northwestern University in Qatar\n| established = 2008\n| type        = Private\n| president   = [[Morton Schapiro]]\n| dean        = [[Everette E. Dennis]]\n| campus      = [[Education City]]\n| mascot      = Willie the Wildcat\n| website     = {{URL |www.qatar.northwestern.edu}}\n| image       = northwestern-university-qatar.png\n| location    = [[Doha, Qatar]]\n| colors      = Purple (official) and white (unofficial)\n}}\n\n'''Northwestern University in Qatar''' (NU-Q) is [[Northwestern University]]\u2019s campus in [[Education City]], [[Doha, Qatar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2008/08/qatar.html|title=Inaugural Classes Begin at Northwestern in Qatar|work=Northwestern University|author=Pat Vaughan Tremmel|date=18 August 2008|accessdate=1 December 2015}}</ref> founded in partnership with [[Qatar Foundation]] in 2008.\n\nNorthwestern University's Qatar campus offers a liberal arts and media education with undergraduate degrees awarded in [[communication]], journalism and strategic communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/provost/policies/handbook/handbook.pdf|title=Northwestern University Handbook|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"studyabroad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.studyabroaduniversities.com/UniversityReview.aspx?University=Northwestern-University-in-Qatar&UniversityId=12874|title=Northwestern University in Qatar|work=studyabroaduniversities.com}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:New NU-Q building.tif|left|thumb|240x240px|Northwestern University in Qatar]]\nHaving been approached in 2006 by the [[Qatar Foundation|Qatar Foundation for Education, Science and Community Development]], Northwestern agreed the following year to open its campus at [[Education City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://civiceducationproject.org/qatar-foundation-and-northwestern-university-agree-on-branch-campus-at-education-city/index.html|title=Civic Education Project|work=civiceducationproject.org}}</ref> The inaugural NU-Q Class of 2012 began studies in August 2008.<ref name=\"thepeninsulaqatar.com\" /> Additional classes have been added each year, and the university has established strong ties with local organizations, partnering with media groups and collaborating with a number of regional initiatives to generate additional educational and professional opportunities for its students.\n\nA number of notable journalists, scholars, and media professionals have addressed students and faculty at Northwestern University in Qatar, including [[Fareed Zakaria]] of CNN's ''Fareed Zakaria GPS''; journalist [[Evan Osnos]] of [[The New Yorker]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulf-times.com/|title=Gulf times- Qatar\u2019s top-selling English daily newspaper - Homepage|website=Gulf-Times|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> television journalist [[Tim Sebastian]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gulf-times.com/error|title=Error Page|website=Gulf-Times|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Iranian-American journalist [[Roxana Saberi]]; Carlos Van Meek, former head of output for Al Jazeera English; Arthur Sulzberger, publisher of the ''New York Times''; Jeff Cole, head of the World Internet Project; [[Rami George Khouri|Rami Khouri]], editor of the ''Beirut Daily Star'', and [[Sophia Al Maria]], author and filmmaker.\n\nThe university graduated its first class in spring 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ida.gov.sg/doc/About%20us/About_Us_Level2/20071005103551/02_Digital_Media_and_Entertainment.pdf|title=IDA|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Academic Programs==\nThe curriculum leading to the award of the Bachelor of Science in Communication degree is based on that of the [[Northwestern University School of Communication]] at Northwestern's Evanston campus. Communication students at NU-Q pursue a major in Media Industries and Technologies, which combines elements of the Communication Studies and Radio/TV/Film majors offered at the Northwestern University home campus in the United States.<ref name=\"thepeninsulaqatar.com\">{{cite web|url=http://archive.thepeninsulaqatar.com/component/content/article/349-qatar-newsarchive/83702.html|title=The Peninsula|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Class at Northwestern University in Qatar.jpg|left|thumb|240x240px|Class at Northwestern University in Qatar]]\nThe curriculum leading to the award of the Bachelor of Science in Journalism degree draws on that of the [[Medill School of Journalism|Medill School of Journalism, Media, Integrated Marketing Communications]] at Northwestern's Evanston campus. This program is accredited by the Accrediting Council on Education in Journalism and Mass Communication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2009/02/qatar.html|title=Taking Northwestern Overseas: Campus Life in Qatar: Northwestern University News|work=northwestern.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ku.edu/~acejmc/STUDENT/PROGLIST.SHTML|title=ACEJMC-accredited programs|work=ku.edu|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726094439/http://www2.ku.edu/~acejmc/STUDENT/PROGLIST.SHTML|archivedate=2014-07-26}}</ref> Liberal arts courses are provided by Northwestern's [[Weinberg College of Arts and Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zawya.com/story.cfm/sidZAWYA20100106072004/Three%20Endowed%20Professorships%20To%20Be%20Named%20After%20Emir%20Of%20Qatar|title=Zawya|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nNU-Q courses are modeled closely on those offered at Northwestern University campus in the United States, although adjustments have been made because the Qatar campus courses are taught in a 15-week semester system, rather than a 10-week quarter system.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ameinfo.com/206867.html|title=Business Real Estate News - Technology - Travel Guide|website=www.ameinfo.com|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"northwestern\">{{cite web|url=http://qatar-news.northwestern.edu/2011/06/junior-from-qatar-campus-reflects-on-two-quarters-in-evanston/|title=Northwestern University in Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Additionally, courses with particular relevance to the region are offered at NU-Q.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.explore-qatar.com/qatar-today/new-face-journalism|title=Explore Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> In 2012, NU-Q secured permission from the Board of Trustees to make its own academic appointments.<ref name=\"northwestern.edu\">[http://qatar-news.northwestern.edu/year-in-review-2012-13/]</ref>\nNU-Q's academic programs provide various opportunities for students to participate in international programs. Students in the Journalism and Strategic Communication Program are required to complete a junior year residency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/academics/journalism-program/journalism-residency.html|title=Northwestern University in Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Juniors in the Communication Program are eligible to apply for the Evanston exchange.<ref name=\"northwestern\" /> Shorter international academic trips are offered at various times throughout the year. Past destinations have included [[Turkey]], [[Switzerland]], [[Italy]], [[South Africa]], [[France]], [[India]] and the [[United States|USA]]. All students are eligible their sophomore year to apply for a one-week trip to the [[Northwestern University]] Evanston campus, which takes place in May of each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/academics/journalism-program/reporting-trips.html|title=Northwestern university in Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Northwestern University in Qatar foyer.jpg|thumb|240x240px|Northwestern University in Qatar campus]]\nNU-Q students can access courses at the five other American universities located in [[Education City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qf.org.qa/news-center/news/news-details?item=130|title=Qatar Foundation|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nNorthwestern's Qatar Campus is one of the best journalism and communication schools in the world. Degrees awarded by Northwestern University's Qatar campus are accredited by the Higher Learning Commission of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]].\n\n=== Pre-College Programs ===\nNU-Q offers an annual [http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/education/pre-college-programs/summer-media-institute/ summer media program to high school students] combining aspects of the Journalism and Strategic Communication and Communication Programs. NU-Q also offers workshops to high school students periodically throughout the school year.\n\n== Funding ==\nSimilar to other universities with campuses in Education City, Northwestern's facilities are entirely paid for by Qatar. In 2014, Northwestern received $45.3 million to run the Doha campus.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/in-qatars-education-city-us-colleges-are-building-an-academic-oasis/2015/12/06/6b538702-8e01-11e5-ae1f-af46b7df8483_story.html|title=In Qatar\u2019s Education City, U.S. colleges are building an academic oasis|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> Also like other Doha campuses of U.S. universities, Qatari students at Northwestern have their tuition covered by Qatar. Students of other nationalities either pay for their own tuition or can sometimes receive scholarship money. {{As of|2016}}, tuition for the school is about $52,000 per year.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/admissions/financial-aid/tuition.html|title=Northwestern University in Qatar Tuition and Fees|last=|first=|date=|website=Northwestern University in Qatar|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:Northwestern University in Qatar newsroom.jpg|left|thumb|240x240px|The University's fully automated newsroom features some of the most advanced technology in broadcast and production.]]\n\n== Facilities ==\n\nNU-Q's permanent home in Education City was designed by American architect [[Antoine Predock]]. Predock traveled around the world, deriving inspiration from desert structures to give NU-Q's new building a look and feel appropriate to Qatar's culture, climate, and location.\n\nNorthwestern moved into its permanent facility in January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/life/new-home.html|title=Northwestern University in Qatar - New Home|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> The four-story building is more than 500,000 square feet and has achieved a [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|LEED]] Gold Certification.\n\nThe university also will soon open The Media Majlis at Northwestern University in Qatar, the first museum in the Arab world dedicated to exploring the content of media, journalism and communication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/mediamajlis/index.html|title=The Media Majlis at Northwestern University in Qatar - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>\n\nLocated on the NU-Q campus, the bilingual (Arabic and English) museum will feature interactive exhibitions, discussion programs and other projects examining media, journalism and communication through global, regional and local/Qatar lenses.&nbsp; An inaugural exhibit will examine a century's worth of film history as shaped by notions of Arab identity. The Media Majlis, Qatar's first university museum, will offer free admission to students, faculty and the public.\n\n== Research ==\nIn 2013, NU-Q launched the school's signature research project, an annual survey of media use in the MENA region. ''Media Use in the Middle East'' in 2013,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://menamediasurvey.northwestern.edu/|title=Media Use in the Middle East 2013 {{!}} Northwestern University in Qatar|website=menamediasurvey.northwestern.edu|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/survey/2014/|title=Entertainment Media Use in the Middle East|website=www.mideastmedia.org|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/survey/2015/|title=Media Use in the Middle East, 2015 \u00b7 Media Use In The Middle East|website=www.mideastmedia.org|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/survey/2016/|title=MEDIA USE IN THE MIDDLE EAST, 2016 \u00b7 Media Use in the Middle East|website=www.mideastmedia.org|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>  and 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/survey/2017/|title=MEDIA USE IN THE MIDDLE EAST, 2017 \u00b7 Media Use in the Middle East, 2017|website=www.mideastmedia.org|access-date=2017-11-14}}</ref> as well the report, ''Media Industries in the Middle East'', 2016,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mideastmedia.org/industry/2016/|title=MENA Media Industry \u00b7 MENA Media Industry|website=www.mideastmedia.org|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> revealed regional attitudes about government censorship, press freedom, the morality of content, entertainment preferences and overall consumption habits, as well as provided an overview of the most prevalent business models across the MENA media landscape. NU-Q's research has been cited by academic institutions and think tanks (e.g., USC Annenberg School Center for the Digital Future,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/2015-World-Internet-Report.pdf|title=2015 World Internet Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Brookings Institution<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/techtank/2015/05/14/the-search-for-media-reality-in-the-arab-middle-east/|title=The search for media reality in the Arab Middle East {{!}} Brookings Institution|date=2017-02-15|newspaper=Brookings|access-date=2017-02-15|language=en-US}}</ref>) as well as news media outlets (e.g.,''Christian Science Monitor'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Global-News/2013/0617/New-poll-shows-growing-Arab-trust-in-regional-press|title=New poll shows growing Arab trust in regional press|last=Zirulnick|first=Ariel|date=2013-06-17|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2017-02-15|issn=0882-7729}}</ref> ''CNN'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/04/23/world/meast/middle-east-hollywood-films-censorship-survey/index.html|title=Hollywood movies in Arab countries: A love and hate relationship|author=Yenni Kwok, for|website=CNN|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> ''The Atlantic'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/04/how-people-in-the-middle-east-actually-use-social-media/275246/|title=How People in the Middle East Actually Use Social Media|last=Wood|first=Everette E. Dennis, Justin D. Martin, and Robb|newspaper=The Atlantic|access-date=2017-02-15|language=en-US}}</ref> ''Al Jazeera'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/02/shrinking-space-media-arab-world-150209093710948.html|title=The shrinking space for media in the Arab world|website=www.aljazeera.com|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> ''Al-Arabiya''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/media/television-and-radio/2016/04/21/Festival-of-Media-Seven-digital-only-radio-stations-coming-to-Dubai-.html|title=Festival of Media: Seven digital-only radio stations coming to Dubai|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>) around the world.\n\n==Students and Student Life==\nApproximately half the student body is Qatari; however, regardless of passport, many students come from Qatar, representing 32 nationalities across the student body. There are about 300 students enrolled in the school.\n\nNU-Q has worked to integrate some western values into its Qatar campus. For example, there are many female students that attend NU-Q. There have been some concerns that this integration, which is not as common in Qatar can be slightly difficult to implement. Qatar adheres to [[Salafi movement|Salafism]], which is one of the most fundamental sects of Islam and dictates all aspects of society and life in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2014/02/11/northwestern-university-s-qatar-campus|title=Northwestern University\u2019s Qatar Campus|website=Chicago Tonight {{!}} WTTW|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/libya/2012-09-19/sources-salafi-conduct|title=The Sources of Salafi Conduct|date=2012-09-20|website=Foreign Affairs|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nNU-Q students have access to the full range of student activities offered to all Education City students, including the Hamad bin Khalifa University Student Center, Recreation Center, clubs, organizations and athletic leagues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/life-nu-q/index.html|title=Campus Life|work=northwestern.edu}}</ref>\n\nNU-Q is the host of many film and production related events, such as THIMUN Qatar Northwestern Film Festival and the NU-Q Student Media and Research Award].\n\nStudents also participate in a wide variety of leadership, service and experiential learning initiatives both in [[Doha]] and internationally.\n\nIn addition, students have access to and participate in a range of athletics, activities, and clubs.\n\n=== Students in the Field ===\n[[File:NU-Q walkway.jpg|left|thumb|280x280px|Northwestern University in Qatar campus]]\nStudent have tackled subjects that are considered controversial in Qatar and throughout the Middle East. One NU-Q graduate was nominated for a student academy award for his film,''100 Steps'', which tells the story of a young boy in Pakistan who finds that his local religious school has served as a front for a radical extremists\u2019 recruitment camp.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2016/08-zali-student-academy-award-nom.html|title=NU-Q graduate nominated for student Oscar - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> ''Convict of 302'', a documentary by two NU-Q students about Pakistan's death penalty and anti-terrorism laws, screened at a consortium sponsored by the Pulitzer Center on Crisis Reporting in Washington, DC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2016/12-Pulitzer-fellows.html|title=NU-Q students screen documentary in Washington, DC - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>\n\nStudents have also written stories about working conditions at local development sites in Qatar, domestic abuse<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/in-qatars-education-city-us-colleges-are-building-an-academic-oasis/2015/12/06/6b538702-8e01-11e5-ae1f-af46b7df8483_story.html|title=In Qatar\u2019s Education City, U.S. colleges are building an academic oasis|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> and women's issues.\n\nAnother NU-Q graduate, Ismaeel Naar, was named Outstanding Young Arab Journalist of the year in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2016/12-Ismaeel-Naar.html|title=NU-Q alum named Outstanding Young Arab Journalist - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>\n\n'''Residency'''\n\nJournalism juniors spend ten weeks working in a professional organization somewhere around the world. Assignments have included the ''Financial Times'', ''National Geographic'', ''Huffington Post'', Grayling Public Relations, Qatar Foundation International and ''Vogue''.The goal of the Journalism Residency is for students to get the kinds of hands-on experience that helps them develop new skills, test old skills, work under deadline pressure, hone their news judgment, sharpen their fact-checking and research skills, build confidence in their capabilities and explore new career paths not previously considered. This is a required component of the B.S. in journalism degree program.\n\n'''Academic Trips'''\n\nThis program is open to NU-Q students and assists them with learning about how organizations work in other countries. Previous trips have included Turkey, Switzerland, Italy, United Kingdom and the United States.\n\n'''Service Learning and Leadership'''\n\nNU-Q students can participate in annual Spring Break Service Learning Trips to global destinations. The goal of the trips are to connect students to the needs of the larger worldwide community, provide insight and understanding of the historical and socio-political context of the visited country, and build a strong sense of global citizenship and commitment. Students complete assigned projects and reflections as part of the experience. Trip destinations have included Brazil, China, India, Morocco, South Africa, Tunisia, Zambia, and more.\n\n'''Evanston Exchange'''\n\nStudents who are a pursuing the BS degree in communication can participate in the Evanston Communication Exchange Program during spring semester of their junior year, where they study at Northwestern's home campus, located near Chicago in Evanston, Illinois, USA.\n\n==Leadership==\nThe leadership of NU-Q is appointed by the Northwestern University Provost, in consultation with the Qatar Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynorthwestern.com/campus/international-search-for-nu-q-dean-john-margolis-replacement-begins-1.2265477|title=Daily Northwestern|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Craig LaMay is the acting dean. An educator, author and media expert, NU-Q's dean Dr. Everette E. Dennis was appointed in June 2011. The founding dean was Dr. John Margolis, an associate provost at Northwestern University who served from 2008 to 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynorthwestern.com/campus/founding-dean-of-northwestern-in-qatar-retires-1.2428764|title=Daily Northwestern|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynorthwestern.com/campus/new-nu-q-dean-hopes-to-mature-institution-1.2603108|title=Daily Northwestern|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> Gregory Ferrell Lowe is director of the Communication Program. Mary Dedinsky is director of the Journalism and Strategic Communication Program. Hariclea Zengos is senior associate dean for research. Kathleen Hewett-Smith is director of the Liberal Arts program. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/about/leadership.html|title=Leadership - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|access-date=2016-10-30}}</ref>\n\nThe NU-Q staff provide the range of support services expected in an American college or university, including professionally staffed offices for admissions, academic and personal counseling, student activities, student records, information technology, human resources, finance, marketing/public relations, and facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/about/our-people/staff/index.html|title=Northwestern University in Qatar|publisher=|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> The collections of the professionally staffed NU-Q library focus on media issues, and students and faculty also have access to all electronic resources available at the Northwestern University Evanston campus and to the services of inter-library loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.library.northwestern.edu/libraries-collections/qatar-campus/library-services|title=Qatar Library Services|work=northwestern.edu}}</ref> A production facilities department provides support for the media-intensive work of students and faculty at NU-Q.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedailyq.org/blog/2011/02/09/nu-q-connects-with-qatar-high-school-students/|title=NU-Q connects with Qatar high school students|work=thedailyq.org}}</ref>\n\n==Faculty==\nThere are 38 faculty members at NU-Q.\n\nMany of the faculty and instructors at NU-Q are not tenured which puts some limits on academic freedom for the professors. This leaves these professors answerable to the NU-Q Dean, a situation that is not dissimilar to faculty members at Northwestern's Evanston Campus. In Qatar, however, a report by Stephen Eiesenman, former President of Northwestern Faculty Senate, pointed out that the Dean has much more authority than in the United States. Additionally, if a faculty member is no longer employed by NU-Q, they must leave the country, forcing them to uproot their lives there, a situation which no doubt puts pressure on the faculty member to work within the confines of a more limited set of academic and intellectual freedoms. Additionally, faculty members at NU-Q are not eligible for tenure unless they are visiting from the Evanston or Chicago campuses.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMany professors at Doha campuses of U.S. universities are incentivized to trade in their teaching positions in the U.S. for ones in Qatar with a salary premium, housing arrangements and research funding.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Community ==\nIn addition to its core mission of providing undergraduate education to its students, NU-Q seeks to serve as a regional center for issues related to communication and journalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2010/12/nuq-dean-everette-dennis.html|title=Everette E. Dennis Named Dean of Northwestern University in Qatar: Northwestern University News|work=northwestern.edu}}</ref> Often in collaboration with local, regional, or international organizations, NU-Q sponsors seminars and colloquia on topics related to the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ameinfo.com/189743.html|title=Business Real Estate News - Technology - Travel Guide|website=www.ameinfo.com|accessdate=2 June 2019}}</ref> NU-Q also sponsors short, non-credit programs for pre-college students, which are designed to expose them to developments in media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/qatar/465-nu-q-reaches-out-to-local-high-schools.html|title=The Peninsula Qatar - NU-Q reaches out to local high schools|work=thepeninsulaqatar.com}}</ref>\n\nOutside of the NU-Q and Education City communities, freedom of speech is highly limited and anyone who threatened \u201csocial values\u201d or Qatar's \u201cgeneral order\u201d through any forms of news, photos, videos or audio recordings can be sentenced to prison. A report by the former President of the Northwestern University Faculty Senate conducted during his tenure as President highlighted that these implicit community values seem to be ingrained in the students, who seemed to willingly comply with these restrictions both intentionally and unintentionally.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Partnerships ==\nNU-Q has undertaken several initiatives in media education and community outreach. In 2013, NU-Q began the biannual Qatar Media Industries Forum (QMIF), bringing together top representatives in publishing, electronic media, digital media, public relations and advertising to discuss and assess the present and future of Qatar's media landscape.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/events/media-industries-forum/|title=Qatar Media Industries Forum - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref> In 2012, the school also established separate partnerships with the [[Doha Film Institute]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.qatarisbooming.com/article/nu-q-partners-doha-film-institute-support-local-media-year%E2%80%99s-dtff|title=NU-Q partners with Doha Film Institute to support local media at this year\u2019s DTFF|last=editor_CM|date=2012-11-03|newspaper=Qatar is Booming|access-date=2017-02-15|language=en}}</ref> and [[Al Jazeera Media Network|Al Jazeera Network]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/docs/publications/annual-report/2012-13-Annual-Report.pdf|title=Unifying Northwestern University in Qatar: Year in Review 2012-2013|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> NU-Q also partners with the [[Qatar Computing Research Institute|Qatar Computer Research Institute]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2016/02-mou-qcri.html|title=NU-Q signs landmark MOU with QCRI for media industry research and knowledge sharing - Northwestern University in Qatar|website=www.qatar.northwestern.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-02-15}}</ref>\n\n== Criticisms ==\nNorthwestern, as with all other U.S. universities with campuses in Doha has been the subject of ongoing criticism of whether a campus in Doha is an appropriate endeavor. In an interview with ''Gulf News Journal'', Herbert London, president of the London Center for Policy Research and a senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute, said \u201cuniversities I think have compromised themselves\u201d by having campuses in a country like Qatar where academic freedom and freedom of the press are severely limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gulfnewsjournal.com/stories/510548507-roots-of-american-universities-grow-deeper-in-qatar-drawing-criticism|title=Roots of American universities grow deeper in Qatar, drawing criticism|last=|first=|date=2015-06-08|website=Gulf News Journal|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nAlong with other universities with campuses in Qatar, Northwestern has received criticism for accepting money from Qatar due to their alleged support of [[terrorism]] worldwide and their abysmal human rights record, especially in the lead up to the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]]. Some question if universities who profit from campuses in Qatar are thereby complicit in Qatar's alleged sponsorship of terrorism and human rights abuses.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gulfnewsjournal.com/stories/510712102-advocate-questions-motive-behind-qatar-s-financial-ties-to-u-s-colleges|title=Advocate questions motive behind Qatar's financial ties to U.S. colleges|last=|first=|date=2016-04-08|website=Gulf News Journal|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gulfnewsjournal.com/stories/510639673-while-u-s-universities-see-dollar-signs-in-qatari-partnerships-some-cry-foul|title=While U.S. universities see dollar signs in Qatari partnerships, some cry foul|last=|first=|date=2015-09-24|website=Gulf News Journal|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\n===Freedom of Speech===\nConcerns have been raised over whether journalism can be taught effectively in a country with limited freedom of expression and where reports of censorship arise from time to time.  Additionally, some members of Northwestern's faculty have expressed \u201cdissatisfaction with the academic and free speech protections\u201d. In an interview with the Washington Post, former Northwestern Faculty Senate President, Stephen Eisenman, said that \u201cteaching journalism as an enterprise in which you must first learn what not to ask, is no kind of journalism instruction at all\u201d and continued that at NU-Q this was \u201clikely a matter of encouraging some enquiries and making others strange, awkward, rude or unserious\u201d.<ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2015/12/17/northwestern-professor-raises-questions-about-its-branch-in-qatar/|title=Northwestern professor raises questions about its branch in Qatar|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref><ref name=\":3\"/><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2016/02/23/northwestern-university-will-stay-another-decade-in-qatar/|title=Northwestern University will stay a decade longer in Qatar|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nIn an article by The Washington Post, Susan Dun, an assistant professor of communication at NU-Q said that some professors do exercise caution with statements, written work, or speeches that may reach a wider audience than just the Education City community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2015/12/17/can-u-s-universities-thrive-in-the-persian-gulf-these-scholars-say-yes/|title=Can U.S. universities thrive in the Persian Gulf? These scholars say yes.|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref>\n\nMohanalakashmi Rajakumar, who taught English at Northwestern, VCU and Georgetown in Qatar published a book called \u201cLove Comes Later\u201d that was banned by Qatar in 2015 with no explanation due to the country's strict censorship policies.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nStudents at Northwestern have said that they face challenges due to the lack of first amendment rights protecting the media. Students have been harassed and intimidated when trying to capture images that would be considered routine or not offensive in the U.S. Some faculty members maintain that this teaches students persistence and creativity in overcoming obstacles to report on a story.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEverette Dennis, the dean of NU-Q led a six-nation survey in 2015 that was financed by the Qatar National Research Fund and asked questions such as if people think their country is \u201cheaded in the right direction\u201d. While the UAE, Egypt, Tunisia, Lebanon and Saudi Arabia all had answers to the question, there was no data from Qatar as the government blocked the question from being asked to survey participants.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.qatar.northwestern.edu/ Northwestern University in Qatar] official website\n\n{{Northwestern}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2008]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Education City]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northwestern_University_in_Qatar"}
{"title_page": "Northrise University", "text_new": "{{infobox university\n|name=        Northrise University\n|image_name= Northrise University Logo.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|motto=       Being excellent at what is good!\n|president=   Dr. Moffat Zimba\n|established= 2003\n|type=        Private - Christ-centered\n|faculty=     77\n|students=    700\n|colors=      Black, Burgundy, white and orange\n|city=        [[Ndola]]\n|country=     [[Zambia]]\n|website=  [http://www.northriseuniversity.com/ Official website]\n}}\n'''Northrise University''' is a private, [[Christianity|Christian]], university in [[Ndola]], [[Zambia]] in [[Sub-Saharan]] [[Africa]]. It was founded in 2003 by Dr Moffat Zimba and Mrs Doreen Zimba.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.moe.gov.zm/index.php/component/content/article/54-directory/146-universities | title=LIST OF RECOGNISED UNIVERSITIES IN ZAMBIA 2015 | publisher=Republic of Zambia Ministry of General Education | accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Waters2008\">{{cite book|author=Bella Waters|title=Zambia in Pictures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x3TvZ6c9i3EC&pg=PA43|accessdate=27 October 2017|date=1 September 2008|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|isbn=978-1-57505-955-6|pages=43\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Musambachime2016\">{{cite book|author=Mwelwa C. Musambachime|title=One Zambia, One Nation, One Country|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fQX3CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT571|accessdate=27 October 2017|date=7 April 2016|publisher=Xlibris UK|isbn=978-1-5144-6228-7|pages=571\u2013}}{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Teferra2013\">{{cite book|author=D. Teferra|title=Funding Higher Education in Sub-Saharan Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2YIhAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT307|accessdate=27 October 2017|date=8 October 2013|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-137-34578-3|pages=307\u2013}}</ref>\n\nNU has local and international students who receive training in academic disciplines at undergraduate and postgraduate levels. While Northrise offers a nationally accredited <ref>{{cite web|title= Accreditation | url= http://www.northriseuniversity.com/accreditation.php/ |publisher= Northrise University |accessdate= 29 October 2009 }}</ref> education that is founded upon Christian principles, the university accepts students of all faiths. Northrise University as at August 16, 2017 has 700 students and 77 academic faculty members. The university has produced a  total of 314 graduates working in different sectors of Zambia's economy.\n\nThe university is in partnership with [[Dordt College]] <ref>{{cite web|title= The Andreas Center offers new opportunities. The Dordt Voice | url= https://www.dordt.edu/cgi-bin/publications/voice/article.pl?id=665 |publisher= The Dordt Voice |accessdate= 29 October 2009 }}</ref> in [[Sioux Center, Iowa|Sioux Center]], [[Iowa]]; [[California Polytechnic State University]], [[San Luis Obispo]], [[California]], United States; [[Shanghai Normal University]], China; and [[Fontys University of Applied Sciences]] in the [[Netherlands]] and [http://www.baylor.edu Baylor University] in Waco, TX.\n\n==Academic programs==\nNorthrise University offers two-year diplomas and both bachelor's and master's degrees from the Schools of Business and Theology.\n\n===School of Business===\n\n'''Postgraduate Programs''' \n* Master of Business Administration\n\n===Center for Information and Communication Technologies (ICT)===\nThe Center for ICT offers students with computer technology skills.\n\n===Faculty of Law===\n{|-\n| style=\"vertical-align: top;\" | <!-- First Column Begins Here -->\n* Bachelor of Laws (LL.B.)\n|}\n\n==History==\nNorthrise University was founded in 2003. It was conceived in 1988 through the experiences of its founders Doreen and Moffat Zimba. Born in Zambia, Doreen and Moffat suffered from the lack of education opportunities for high school graduates that still characterize their country.  Moffat and Doreen left Zambia to attend a Bible college in Australia. Upon completion, they went to Southern California where Moffat received his Doctorate from [[Fuller Theological Seminary]] and Doreen received her MBA in Technology Management from the [[University of Phoenix]].\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Downtown Campus===\nNorthrise University is in Ndola, Zambia. The campus, in the business centre of the town, is on Buteko Avenue in Caravelle House, opposite the Savoy Hotel.\n\nCaravelle House, wholly owned by Northrise University, is a four-storey building able to cater for 300 students.\n\n===Main Campus===\nThe Main Campus is 8&nbsp;kilometers from town on the [[T3 Road (Zambia)|T3 Road]] ([[Ndola]]-[[Kitwe]] Dual Carriageway).\n\nNorthrise, having been provided with {{convert|640|acre|km2}} of land, has embarked on a $10 million campus project. The construction of the Main Campus structures is underway and the university has completed its first phase that includes a student dormitory block with a capacity of 56 students.\n\nThe campus construction is taking place in phases. After completion it will be able to enroll 1000 students and a total capacity of 300 boarding places.\n\n==Finances==\n\n===Northrise University Initiative===\nNorthrise University Initiative is a [501(c) organization|501(c)3] California non-profit corporation established to support Northrise University in Zambia.\n\n====Student Sponsorship====\nNorthrise University offers opportunities for donors to sponsor students, as most Zambians cannot afford full tuition on their own. Those who receive financial aid are required to contribute to their tuition, which gives students a greater sense of ownership and accomplishment.\n\n===Northrise Farms===\nNorthrise Farms is a wholly owned agricultural unit of Northrise University. The farm provides farm produce for the NU community and the general public. Ultimately, the farm will contribute towards reducing the operating costs of the university, thereby providing an opportunity for students from poor families to attend Northrise University at affordable fees. The farm also provides employment to the community. The establishment of Northrise Farms serves as a foundation for the commencement of the Faculty of Agriculture at Northrise University.\nThe farm provides food for students and staff.\n\nThe farm\u2019s rich soil and high water table, as well as the region\u2019s ideal climate, make it a solid foundation for a future Agricultural program. Through its strategic partnership with California Polytechnic State University, San Luis Obispo, Northrise will provide training to equip students for farming employment. The farm will serve as a working model and consulting center for Zambians looking to establish their own farms.\n\n===Northrise Services===\nNorthrise Services is a company owned by Northrise University. Because of the poor state of the economy, most Zambians cannot afford to pay tuition to attend classes. Since tuition alone cannot fund University operations, Northrise has had to find additional sources of funding other than donations. Therefore, NS was created to help ensure that the university has the financial support it needs to continue.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.northriseuniversity.com/index.php Northrise University website]\n* [http://zambianchronicle.com/2007/10/22/northrise-university-is-this-the-new-ivy-league-for-zambia/ Is this the new ivy league for Zambia]\n{{Universities in Zambia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Zambia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Ndola]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Zambia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Copperbelt Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox University\n|name=        Northrise University\n|image_name= Northrise University Logo.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|motto=       Being excellent at what is good!\n|president=   Dr. Moffat Zimba\n|established= 2003\n|type=        Private - Christ-centered\n|faculty=     77\n|students=    700\n|colors=      Black, Burgundy, white and orange\n|city=        [[Ndola]]\n|country=     [[Zambia]]\n|website=  [http://www.northriseuniversity.com/ Official website]\n}}\n'''Northrise University''' is a private, [[Christianity|Christian]], university in [[Ndola]], [[Zambia]] in [[Sub-Saharan]] [[Africa]]. It was founded in 2003 by Dr Moffat Zimba and Mrs Doreen Zimba.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.moe.gov.zm/index.php/component/content/article/54-directory/146-universities | title=LIST OF RECOGNISED UNIVERSITIES IN ZAMBIA 2015 | publisher=Republic of Zambia Ministry of General Education | accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Waters2008\">{{cite book|author=Bella Waters|title=Zambia in Pictures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x3TvZ6c9i3EC&pg=PA43|accessdate=27 October 2017|date=1 September 2008|publisher=Twenty-First Century Books|isbn=978-1-57505-955-6|pages=43\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Musambachime2016\">{{cite book|author=Mwelwa C. Musambachime|title=One Zambia, One Nation, One Country|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fQX3CwAAQBAJ&pg=PT571|accessdate=27 October 2017|date=7 April 2016|publisher=Xlibris UK|isbn=978-1-5144-6228-7|pages=571\u2013}}{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=January 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Teferra2013\">{{cite book|author=D. Teferra|title=Funding Higher Education in Sub-Saharan Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2YIhAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT307|accessdate=27 October 2017|date=8 October 2013|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-137-34578-3|pages=307\u2013}}</ref>\n\nNU has local and international students who receive training in academic disciplines at undergraduate and postgraduate levels. While Northrise offers a nationally accredited <ref>{{cite web|title= Accreditation | url= http://www.northriseuniversity.com/accreditation.php/ |publisher= Northrise University |accessdate= 29 October 2009 }}</ref> education that is founded upon Christian principles, the university accepts students of all faiths. Northrise University as at August 16, 2017 has 700 students and 77 academic faculty members. The university has produced a  total of 314 graduates working in different sectors of Zambia's economy.\n\nThe university is in partnership with [[Dordt College]] <ref>{{cite web|title= The Andreas Center offers new opportunities. The Dordt Voice | url= https://www.dordt.edu/cgi-bin/publications/voice/article.pl?id=665 |publisher= The Dordt Voice |accessdate= 29 October 2009 }}</ref> in [[Sioux Center, Iowa|Sioux Center]], [[Iowa]]; [[California Polytechnic State University]], [[San Luis Obispo]], [[California]], United States; [[Shanghai Normal University]], China; and [[Fontys University of Applied Sciences]] in the [[Netherlands]] and [http://www.baylor.edu Baylor University] in Waco, TX.\n\n==Academic programs==\nNorthrise University offers two-year diplomas and both bachelor's and master's degrees from the Schools of Business and Theology.\n\n===School of Business===\n\n'''Postgraduate Programs''' \n* Master of Business Administration\n\n===Center for Information and Communication Technologies (ICT)===\nThe Center for ICT offers students with computer technology skills.\n\n===Faculty of Law===\n{|-\n| style=\"vertical-align: top;\" | <!-- First Column Begins Here -->\n* Bachelor of Laws (LL.B.)\n|}\n\n==History==\nNorthrise University was founded in 2003. It was conceived in 1988 through the experiences of its founders Doreen and Moffat Zimba. Born in Zambia, Doreen and Moffat suffered from the lack of education opportunities for high school graduates that still characterize their country.  Moffat and Doreen left Zambia to attend a Bible college in Australia. Upon completion, they went to Southern California where Moffat received his Doctorate from [[Fuller Theological Seminary]] and Doreen received her MBA in Technology Management from the [[University of Phoenix]].\n\n==Campus==\n\n===Downtown Campus===\nNorthrise University is in Ndola, Zambia. The campus, in the business centre of the town, is on Buteko Avenue in Caravelle House, opposite the Savoy Hotel.\n\nCaravelle House, wholly owned by Northrise University, is a four-storey building able to cater for 300 students.\n\n===Main Campus===\nThe Main Campus is 8&nbsp;kilometers from town on the [[T3 Road (Zambia)|T3 Road]] ([[Ndola]]-[[Kitwe]] Dual Carriageway).\n\nNorthrise, having been provided with {{convert|640|acre|km2}} of land, has embarked on a $10 million campus project. The construction of the Main Campus structures is underway and the university has completed its first phase that includes a student dormitory block with a capacity of 56 students.\n\nThe campus construction is taking place in phases. After completion it will be able to enroll 1000 students and a total capacity of 300 boarding places.\n\n==Finances==\n\n===Northrise University Initiative===\nNorthrise University Initiative is a [501(c) organization|501(c)3] California non-profit corporation established to support Northrise University in Zambia.\n\n====Student Sponsorship====\nNorthrise University offers opportunities for donors to sponsor students, as most Zambians cannot afford full tuition on their own. Those who receive financial aid are required to contribute to their tuition, which gives students a greater sense of ownership and accomplishment.\n\n===Northrise Farms===\nNorthrise Farms is a wholly owned agricultural unit of Northrise University. The farm provides farm produce for the NU community and the general public. Ultimately, the farm will contribute towards reducing the operating costs of the university, thereby providing an opportunity for students from poor families to attend Northrise University at affordable fees. The farm also provides employment to the community. The establishment of Northrise Farms serves as a foundation for the commencement of the Faculty of Agriculture at Northrise University.\nThe farm provides food for students and staff.\n\nThe farm\u2019s rich soil and high water table, as well as the region\u2019s ideal climate, make it a solid foundation for a future Agricultural program. Through its strategic partnership with California Polytechnic State University, San Luis Obispo, Northrise will provide training to equip students for farming employment. The farm will serve as a working model and consulting center for Zambians looking to establish their own farms.\n\n===Northrise Services===\nNorthrise Services is a company owned by Northrise University. Because of the poor state of the economy, most Zambians cannot afford to pay tuition to attend classes. Since tuition alone cannot fund University operations, Northrise has had to find additional sources of funding other than donations. Therefore, NS was created to help ensure that the university has the financial support it needs to continue.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.northriseuniversity.com/index.php Northrise University website]\n* [http://zambianchronicle.com/2007/10/22/northrise-university-is-this-the-new-ivy-league-for-zambia/ Is this the new ivy league for Zambia]\n{{Universities in Zambia}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Zambia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Ndola]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Zambia]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Copperbelt Province]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northrise_University"}
